1
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:35,480
I
Patrol Cruiser "IP-T 247" circling out toward

2
00:00:35,480 --> 00:00:41,400
Pluto on leisurely inspection tour to visit
the outpost miners there, was in no hurry

3
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:43,520
at all as she loafed along.

4
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:49,930
Her six-man crew was taking it very easy,
and easy meant two-man watches, and low speed,

5
00:00:49,930 --> 00:00:54,540
to watch for the instrument panel and attend
ship into the bargain.

6
00:00:54,540 --> 00:00:59,150
She was about thirty million miles off Pluto,
just beginning to get in touch with some of

7
00:00:59,150 --> 00:01:06,120
the larger mining stations out there, when
Buck Kendall's turn at the controls came along.

8
00:01:06,120 --> 00:01:10,340
Buck Kendall was one of life's little jokes.

9
00:01:10,340 --> 00:01:14,010
When Nature made him, she was absentminded.

10
00:01:14,010 --> 00:01:20,780
Buck stood six feet two in his stocking feet,
with his usual slight stoop in operation.

11
00:01:20,780 --> 00:01:25,330
When he forgot, and stood up straight, he
loomed about two inches higher.

12
00:01:25,330 --> 00:01:30,980
He had the body and muscles of a dock navvy,
which Nature started out to make.

13
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:36,750
Then she forgot and added something of the
same stuff she put in Sir Francis Drake.

14
00:01:36,750 --> 00:01:42,000
Maybe that made Old Nature nervous, and she
started adding different things.

15
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,520
At any rate, Kendall, as finally turned out,
had a brain that put him in the first rank

16
00:01:47,520 --> 00:01:53,591
of scientists—when he felt like it—the
general constitution of an ostrich and a flair

17
00:01:53,591 --> 00:01:55,490
for gambling.

18
00:01:55,490 --> 00:01:58,469
The present position was due to such a gamble.

19
00:01:58,469 --> 00:02:04,790
An IP man, a friend of his, had made the mistake
of betting him a thousand dollars he wouldn't

20
00:02:04,790 --> 00:02:08,970
get beyond a Captain's bars in the Patrol.

21
00:02:08,970 --> 00:02:14,480
Kendall had liked the idea anyway, and adding
a bit of a bet to it made it irresistible.

22
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:20,620
So, being a very particular kind of a fool,
the glorious kind which old Nature turns out

23
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:27,440
now and then, he left a five million dollar
estate on Long Island, Terra, that same evening,

24
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:30,240
and joined up in the Patrol.

25
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:35,710
The Sir Francis Drake strain had immediately
come forth—and Kendall was having the time

26
00:02:35,710 --> 00:02:37,230
of his life.

27
00:02:37,230 --> 00:02:44,180
In a six-man cruiser, his real work in the
Interplanetary Patrol had started.

28
00:02:44,180 --> 00:02:49,680
He was still in it—but it was his command
now, and a blue circle on his left sleeve

29
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:52,430
gave his lieutenant's rank.

30
00:02:52,430 --> 00:02:57,489
Buck Kendall had immediately proceeded to
enlist in his command the IP man who had made

31
00:02:57,489 --> 00:03:03,040
the mistaken bet, and Rad Cole was on duty
with him now.

32
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:06,760
Cole was the technician of the T-247.

33
00:03:06,760 --> 00:03:12,680
His rank as Technical Engineer was practically
equivalent to Kendall's circle-rank, which

34
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:16,090
made the two more comfortable together.

35
00:03:16,090 --> 00:03:20,220
Cole was listening carefully to the signals
coming through from Pluto.

36
00:03:20,220 --> 00:03:25,020
"That," he decided, "sounds like Tad Nichols'
fist.

37
00:03:25,020 --> 00:03:30,290
You can recognize that broken-down truck-horse
trot of his on the key as far away as you

38
00:03:30,290 --> 00:03:31,450
can hear it."

39
00:03:31,450 --> 00:03:33,019
"Is that what it is?"

40
00:03:33,019 --> 00:03:34,040
sighed Buck.

41
00:03:34,040 --> 00:03:37,049
"I thought it was static mushing him at first.

42
00:03:37,049 --> 00:03:38,590
What's he like?"

43
00:03:38,590 --> 00:03:44,810
"Like all the other damn fools who come out
two billion miles to scratch rock, as if there

44
00:03:44,810 --> 00:03:47,900
weren't enough already on the inner planets.

45
00:03:47,900 --> 00:03:50,439
He's got a rich platinum property.

46
00:03:50,439 --> 00:03:54,800
Sells ninety percent of his output to buy
his power, and the other eleven percent for

47
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:56,120
his clothes and food."

48
00:03:56,120 --> 00:04:02,709
"He must be an efficient miner," suggested
Kendall, "to maintain 101% production like

49
00:04:02,709 --> 00:04:03,709
that."

50
00:04:03,709 --> 00:04:06,720
"No, but his bank account is.

51
00:04:06,720 --> 00:04:10,120
He's figured out that's the most economic
level of production.

52
00:04:10,120 --> 00:04:15,360
If he produces less, he won't be able to pay
for his heating power, and if he produces

53
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:20,739
more, his operation power will burn up his
bank account too fast."

54
00:04:20,739 --> 00:04:23,620
"Hmmm—sensible way to figure.

55
00:04:23,620 --> 00:04:25,290
A man after my own heart.

56
00:04:25,290 --> 00:04:28,550
How does he plan to restock his bank account?"

57
00:04:28,550 --> 00:04:30,830
"By mining on Mercury.

58
00:04:30,830 --> 00:04:33,940
He does it regularly—sort of a commuter.

59
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:36,280
Out here his power bills eat it up.

60
00:04:36,280 --> 00:04:41,340
On Mercury he goes in for potassium, and sells
the power he collects in cooling his dome,

61
00:04:41,340 --> 00:04:42,340
of course.

62
00:04:42,340 --> 00:04:47,260
He's a good miner, and the old fool can make
money down there."

63
00:04:47,260 --> 00:04:53,320
Like any really skilled operator, Cole had
been sending Morse messages while he talked.

64
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:58,540
Now he sat quiet waiting for the reply, glancing
at the chronometer.

65
00:04:58,540 --> 00:05:04,450
"I take it he's not after money—just after
fun," suggested Buck.

66
00:05:04,450 --> 00:05:05,570
"Oh, no.

67
00:05:05,570 --> 00:05:08,670
He's after money," replied Cole gravely.

68
00:05:08,670 --> 00:05:15,030
"You ask him—he's going to make his eternal
fortune yet by striking a real bed of jovium,

69
00:05:15,030 --> 00:05:16,320
and then he'll retire."

70
00:05:16,320 --> 00:05:19,230
"Oh, one of that kind."

71
00:05:19,230 --> 00:05:22,600
"They all are," Cole laughed.

72
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:25,750
"Eternal hope, and the rest of it."

73
00:05:25,750 --> 00:05:27,750
He listened a moment and went on.

74
00:05:27,750 --> 00:05:31,410
"But old Nichols is a first-grade engineer.

75
00:05:31,410 --> 00:05:36,160
He wouldn't be able to remake that bankroll
every time if he wasn't.

76
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:41,320
You'll see his Dome out there on Pluto—it's
always the best on the planet.

77
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:43,030
Tip-top shape.

78
00:05:43,030 --> 00:05:45,680
And he's a bit of an experimenter too.

79
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:48,110
Ah—he's with us."

80
00:05:48,110 --> 00:05:52,560
Nichols' ragged signals were coming through—or
pounding through.

81
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:57,260
They were worse than usual, and at first Kendall
and Cole couldn't make them out.

82
00:05:57,260 --> 00:05:59,970
Then finally they got them in bursts.

83
00:05:59,970 --> 00:06:03,950
The man was excited, and his bad key-work
made it worse.

84
00:06:03,950 --> 00:06:06,300
"—Randing stopped.

85
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:07,880
They got him I think.

86
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:13,780
He said—th—ship as big—a—nsport.

87
00:06:13,780 --> 00:06:18,330
Said it wa—eaded my—ay.

88
00:06:18,330 --> 00:06:33,510
Neutrons—on instruments—he's coming over
the horizon—it's huge—war ship I think—register—instru—neutrons—."

89
00:06:33,510 --> 00:06:36,530
Abruptly the signals were blanked out completely.

90
00:06:36,530 --> 00:06:40,830
Cole and Kendall sat frozen and stiff.

91
00:06:40,830 --> 00:06:45,620
Each looked at the other abruptly, then Kendall
moved.

92
00:06:45,620 --> 00:06:50,970
From the receiver, he ripped out the recording
coil, and instantly jammed it into the analyzer.

93
00:06:50,970 --> 00:06:55,860
He started it through once, then again, then
again, at different tone settings, till he

94
00:06:55,860 --> 00:07:02,140
found a very shrill whine that seemed to clear
up most of Nichols' bad key-work.

95
00:07:02,140 --> 00:07:04,220
"T-247—T-247—Emergency.

96
00:07:04,220 --> 00:07:06,300
Emergency.

97
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:13,160
Randing reports the—over his horizon.

98
00:07:13,160 --> 00:07:17,500
Huge—ip—reign manufacture.

99
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:18,500
Almost spherical.

100
00:07:18,500 --> 00:07:20,470
Randing's stopped.

101
00:07:20,470 --> 00:07:22,440
They got him I think.

102
00:07:22,440 --> 00:07:25,830
He said the ship was as big as a transport.

103
00:07:25,830 --> 00:07:29,600
Said it was headed my way.

104
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:32,410
Neutrons—ont—gister—instruments.

105
00:07:32,410 --> 00:07:35,950
I think—is h—he's coming over the horizon.

106
00:07:35,950 --> 00:07:44,050
It's huge, and a war ship I think—register—instruments—neutrons."

107
00:07:44,050 --> 00:07:46,610
Kendall's finger stabbed out at a button.

108
00:07:46,610 --> 00:07:52,440
Instantly the noise of the other men, wakened
abruptly by the mild shocks, came from behind.

109
00:07:52,440 --> 00:07:56,100
Kendall swung to the controls, and Cole raced
back to the engine room.

110
00:07:56,100 --> 00:08:01,500
The hundred-foot ship shot suddenly forward
under the thrust of her tail ion-rockets.

111
00:08:01,500 --> 00:08:06,870
A blue-red cloud formed slowly behind her
and expanded.

112
00:08:06,870 --> 00:08:10,960
Talbot appeared, and silently took her over
from Kendall.

113
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:13,820
"Stations, men," snapped Kendall.

114
00:08:13,820 --> 00:08:20,200
"Emergency call from a miner of Pluto reporting
a large armed vessel which attacked them."

115
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:24,620
Kendall swung back, and eased himself against
the thrusting acceleration of the over-powered

116
00:08:24,620 --> 00:08:28,150
little ship, toward the engine room.

117
00:08:28,150 --> 00:08:33,969
Cole was bending over his apparatus, making
careful check-ups, closing weapon-circuits.

118
00:08:33,969 --> 00:08:39,409
No window gave view of space here; on the
left was the tiny tender's pocket, on the

119
00:08:39,409 --> 00:08:44,720
right, above and below the great water tanks
that fed the ion-rockets, behind the rockets

120
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:46,250
themselves.

121
00:08:46,250 --> 00:08:52,060
The tungsten metal walls were cold and gray
under the ship lights; the hunched bulks of

122
00:08:52,060 --> 00:08:55,740
the apparatus crowded the tiny room.

123
00:08:55,740 --> 00:08:58,740
Gigantic racked accumulators huddled in the
corners.

124
00:08:58,740 --> 00:09:04,339
Martin and Garnet swung into position in the
fighting-tanks just ahead of the power rooms;

125
00:09:04,339 --> 00:09:10,139
Canning slid rapidly through the engine room,
oozed through a tiny door, and took up his

126
00:09:10,139 --> 00:09:15,250
position in the stern-chamber, seated half-over
the great ion-rocket sheath.

127
00:09:15,250 --> 00:09:20,430
"Ready in positions, Captain Kendall," called
the war-pilot as the little green lights appeared

128
00:09:20,430 --> 00:09:22,069
on his board.

129
00:09:22,069 --> 00:09:25,800
"Test discharges on maximum," ordered Kendall.

130
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:26,800
He turned to Cole.

131
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:28,800
"You start the automatic key?"

132
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:30,220
"Right, Captain."

133
00:09:30,220 --> 00:09:31,630
"All shipshape?"

134
00:09:31,630 --> 00:09:34,460
"Right as can be.

135
00:09:34,460 --> 00:09:37,000
Accumulators at thirty-seven per cent, thanks
to the loaf out here.

136
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:41,709
They ought to pick up our signal back on Jupiter,
he's nearest now.

137
00:09:41,709 --> 00:09:43,910
The station on Europa will get it."

138
00:09:43,910 --> 00:09:47,879
"Talbot—we are only to investigate if the
ship is as reported.

139
00:09:47,879 --> 00:09:51,290
Have you seen any signs of her?"

140
00:09:51,290 --> 00:09:53,490
"No sir, and the signals are blank."

141
00:09:53,490 --> 00:09:55,740
"I'll work from here."

142
00:09:55,740 --> 00:09:58,949
Kendall took his position at the commanding
control.

143
00:09:58,949 --> 00:10:02,050
Cole made way for him, and moved to the power
board.

144
00:10:02,050 --> 00:10:06,990
One by one he tested the automatic doors,
the pressure bulkheads.

145
00:10:06,990 --> 00:10:11,120
Kendall watched the instruments as one after
another of the weapons were tested on momentary

146
00:10:11,120 --> 00:10:16,360
full discharge—titanic flames of five million
volt protons.

147
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:20,800
Then the ship thudded to the chatter of the
Garnell rifles.

148
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:25,589
Tensely the men watched the planet ahead,
white, yet barely visible in the weak sunlight

149
00:10:25,589 --> 00:10:27,060
so far out.

150
00:10:27,060 --> 00:10:31,740
It was swimming slowly nearer as the tiny
ship gathered speed.

151
00:10:31,740 --> 00:10:35,889
Kendall cast a glance over his detector-instruments.

152
00:10:35,889 --> 00:10:41,480
The radio network was undisturbed, the magnetic
and electric fields recognized only the slight

153
00:10:41,480 --> 00:10:45,040
disturbances occasioned by the planet itself.

154
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:48,279
There was nothing, noth—

155
00:10:48,279 --> 00:10:55,670
Five hundred miles away, a gigantic ship came
into instantaneous being.

156
00:10:55,670 --> 00:11:02,899
Simultaneously, and instantaneously, the various
detector systems howled their warnings.

157
00:11:02,899 --> 00:11:07,749
Kendall gasped as the thing appeared on his
view screen, with the scale-lines below.

158
00:11:07,749 --> 00:11:09,420
The scale must be cock-eyed.

159
00:11:09,420 --> 00:11:15,360
They said the ship was fifteen hundred feet
in diameter, and two thousand long!

160
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:19,499
"Retreat," ordered Kendall, "at maximum acceleration."

161
00:11:19,499 --> 00:11:23,040
Talbot was already acting.

162
00:11:23,040 --> 00:11:26,350
The gyroscopes hummed in their castings, and
the motors creaked.

163
00:11:26,350 --> 00:11:33,930
The T-247 spun on her axis, and abruptly the
acceleration built up as the ion-rockets began

164
00:11:33,930 --> 00:11:34,930
to shudder.

165
00:11:34,930 --> 00:11:39,259
A faint smell of "heat" began to creep out
of the converter.

166
00:11:39,259 --> 00:11:44,769
Immense "weight" built up, and pressed the
men into their specially designed seats—

167
00:11:44,769 --> 00:11:52,660
The gigantic ship across the way turned slowly,
and seemed to stare at the T-247.

168
00:11:52,660 --> 00:11:59,490
Then it darted toward them at incredible speed
till the poor little T-247 seemed to be standing

169
00:11:59,490 --> 00:12:01,230
still, as sailors say.

170
00:12:01,230 --> 00:12:07,440
The stranger was so gigantic now, the screens
could not show all of him.

171
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:10,629
"God, Buck—he's going to take us!"

172
00:12:10,629 --> 00:12:18,629
Simultaneously, the T-247 rolled, and from
her broke every possible stream of destruction.

173
00:12:18,629 --> 00:12:24,339
The ion-rocket flames swirled abruptly toward
her, the proton-guns whined their song of

174
00:12:24,339 --> 00:12:30,870
death in their housings, and the heavy pounding
shudder of the Garnell guns racked the ship.

175
00:12:30,870 --> 00:12:35,699
Strangely, Kendall suddenly noticed, there
was a stillness in the ship.

176
00:12:35,699 --> 00:12:43,210
The guns and the rays were still going—but
the little human sounds seemed abruptly gone.

177
00:12:43,210 --> 00:12:47,860
"Talbot—Garnet—" Only silence answered
him.

178
00:12:47,860 --> 00:12:51,649
Cole looked across at him in sudden white-faced
amazement.

179
00:12:51,649 --> 00:12:56,600
"They're gone—" gasped Cole.

180
00:12:56,600 --> 00:12:59,300
Kendall stood paralyzed for thirty seconds.

181
00:12:59,300 --> 00:13:02,170
Then suddenly he seemed to come to life.

182
00:13:02,170 --> 00:13:03,420
"Neutrons!

183
00:13:03,420 --> 00:13:05,639
Neutrons—and water tanks!

184
00:13:05,639 --> 00:13:09,649
Old Nichols was right—" He turned to his
friend.

185
00:13:09,649 --> 00:13:11,509
"Cole—the tender—quick."

186
00:13:11,509 --> 00:13:13,760
He darted a glance at the screen.

187
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:17,420
The giant ship still lay alongside.

188
00:13:17,420 --> 00:13:21,990
A wash of ions was curling around her, splitting,
and passing on.

189
00:13:21,990 --> 00:13:29,550
The pinprick explosions of the Garnell shells
dotted space around her—but never on her.

190
00:13:29,550 --> 00:13:32,499
Cole was already racing for the tender lock.

191
00:13:32,499 --> 00:13:35,560
In an instant Kendall piled in after him.

192
00:13:35,560 --> 00:13:41,899
The tiny ship, scarcely ten feet long, was
powered for flights of only two hours acceleration,

193
00:13:41,899 --> 00:13:48,980
and had oxygen for but twenty-four hours for
six men, seventy-two hours for two men—maybe.

194
00:13:48,980 --> 00:13:53,910
The heavy door was slammed shut behind them,
as Cole seated himself at the panel.

195
00:13:53,910 --> 00:13:58,820
He depressed a lever, and a sudden smooth
push shot them away from the T-247.

196
00:13:58,820 --> 00:14:06,740
"DON'T!" called Kendall sharply as Cole reached
for the ion-rocket control.

197
00:14:06,740 --> 00:14:09,230
"Douse those lights!"

198
00:14:09,230 --> 00:14:11,610
The ship was dark in dark space.

199
00:14:11,610 --> 00:14:18,119
The lighted hull of the T-247 drifted away
from the little tender—further and further

200
00:14:18,119 --> 00:14:21,910
till the giant ship on the far side became
visible.

201
00:14:21,910 --> 00:14:25,230
"Not a light—not a sign of fields in operation."

202
00:14:25,230 --> 00:14:29,019
Kendall said, unconsciously speaking softly.

203
00:14:29,019 --> 00:14:33,949
"This thing is so tiny, that it may escape
their observation in the fields of the T-247

204
00:14:33,949 --> 00:14:35,660
and Pluto down there.

205
00:14:35,660 --> 00:14:37,639
It's our only hope."

206
00:14:37,639 --> 00:14:39,850
"What happened?

207
00:14:39,850 --> 00:14:45,040
How in the name of the planets did they kill
those men without a sound, without a flash,

208
00:14:45,040 --> 00:14:48,230
and without even warning us, or injuring us?"

209
00:14:48,230 --> 00:14:50,660
"Neutrons—don't you see?"

210
00:14:50,660 --> 00:14:52,589
"Frankly, I don't.

211
00:14:52,589 --> 00:14:56,439
I'm no scientist—merely a technician.

212
00:14:56,439 --> 00:14:59,820
Neutrons aren't used in any process I've run
across."

213
00:14:59,820 --> 00:15:03,649
"Well, remember they're uncharged, tiny things.

214
00:15:03,649 --> 00:15:07,209
Small as protons, but without electric field.

215
00:15:07,209 --> 00:15:11,889
The result is they pass right through an ordinary
atom without being stopped unless they make

216
00:15:11,889 --> 00:15:13,379
a direct hit.

217
00:15:13,379 --> 00:15:19,119
Tungsten, while it has a beautifully high
melting point, is mostly open space, and a

218
00:15:19,119 --> 00:15:23,380
neutron just sails right through it, or any
heavy atom.

219
00:15:23,380 --> 00:15:27,819
Light atoms stop neutrons better—there's
less open space in 'em.

220
00:15:27,819 --> 00:15:28,990
Hydrogen is best.

221
00:15:28,990 --> 00:15:35,470
Well—a man is made up mostly of light elements,
and a man stops those neutrons—it isn't

222
00:15:35,470 --> 00:15:40,160
surprising it killed those other fellows invisibly,
and without a sound."

223
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:44,089
"You mean they bathed that ship in neutrons?"

224
00:15:44,089 --> 00:15:46,499
"Shot it full of 'em.

225
00:15:46,499 --> 00:15:49,910
Just like our proton guns, only sending neutrons."

226
00:15:49,910 --> 00:15:52,639
"Well, why weren't we killed too?"

227
00:15:52,639 --> 00:15:56,339
"'Water stops neutrons,' I said.

228
00:15:56,339 --> 00:15:58,559
Figure it out."

229
00:15:58,559 --> 00:16:02,170
"The rocket-water tanks—all around us!

230
00:16:02,170 --> 00:16:05,440
Great masses of water—" gasped Cole.

231
00:16:05,440 --> 00:16:07,589
"That saved us?"

232
00:16:07,589 --> 00:16:08,589
"Right.

233
00:16:08,589 --> 00:16:11,279
I wonder if they've spotted us."

234
00:16:11,279 --> 00:16:14,540
The stranger ship was moving slowly in relation
to the T-247.

235
00:16:14,540 --> 00:16:22,519
Suddenly the motion changed, the stranger
spun—and a giant lock appeared in her side,

236
00:16:22,519 --> 00:16:23,519
opened.

237
00:16:23,519 --> 00:16:30,420
The T-247 began to move, floated more and
more rapidly straight for the lock.

238
00:16:30,420 --> 00:16:36,529
Her various weapons had stopped operating
now, the hoppers of the Garnell guns exhausted,

239
00:16:36,529 --> 00:16:41,290
the charge of the accumulators aboard the
ship down so low the proton guns had died

240
00:16:41,290 --> 00:16:42,620
out.

241
00:16:42,620 --> 00:16:46,339
"Lord—they're taking the whole ship!"

242
00:16:46,339 --> 00:16:50,839
"Say—Cole, is that any ship you ever heard
of before?

243
00:16:50,839 --> 00:16:52,779
I don't think that's just a pirate!"

244
00:16:52,779 --> 00:16:55,720
"Not a pirate—what then?"

245
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:59,690
"How'd he get inside our detector screens
so fast?

246
00:16:59,690 --> 00:17:06,900
Watch—he'll either leave, or come after
us—" The T-247 had settled inside the lock

247
00:17:06,900 --> 00:17:11,100
now, and the great metal door closed after
it.

248
00:17:11,100 --> 00:17:16,600
The whole patrol ship had been swallowed by
a giant.

249
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:21,660
Kendall was sketching swiftly on a notebook,
watching the vast ship closely, putting down

250
00:17:21,660 --> 00:17:24,820
a record of its lines, and formation.

251
00:17:24,820 --> 00:17:29,770
He glanced up at it, and then down for a few
more lines, and up at it—

252
00:17:29,770 --> 00:17:32,260
The stranger ship abruptly dwindled.

253
00:17:32,260 --> 00:17:38,660
It dwindled with incredible speed, rushing
off along the line of sight at an impossible

254
00:17:38,660 --> 00:17:44,380
velocity, and abruptly clicking out of sight,
like an image on a movie-film that has been

255
00:17:44,380 --> 00:17:48,520
cut, and repaired after the scene that showed
the final disappearance.

256
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:51,680
"Cole—Cole—did you get that?

257
00:17:51,680 --> 00:17:56,920
Did you see—do you understand what happened?"

258
00:17:56,920 --> 00:17:58,900
Kendall was excitedly shouting now.

259
00:17:58,900 --> 00:18:01,620
"He missed us," Cole sighed.

260
00:18:01,620 --> 00:18:08,010
"It's a wonder—hanging out here in space,
with the protector of the T-247's fields gone."

261
00:18:08,010 --> 00:18:11,870
"No, no, you asteroid—that's not it.

262
00:18:11,870 --> 00:18:16,470
He went off faster than light itself!"

263
00:18:16,470 --> 00:18:18,760
"Eh—what?

264
00:18:18,760 --> 00:18:19,760
Faster than light?

265
00:18:19,760 --> 00:18:20,930
That can't be done—"

266
00:18:20,930 --> 00:18:24,650
"He did it, I know he did.

267
00:18:24,650 --> 00:18:27,450
That's how he got inside our screens.

268
00:18:27,450 --> 00:18:32,500
He came inside faster than the warning message
could relay back the information.

269
00:18:32,500 --> 00:18:38,560
Didn't you see him accelerate to an impossible
speed in an impossible time?

270
00:18:38,560 --> 00:18:43,050
Didn't you see how he just vanished as he
exceeded the speed of light, and stopped reflecting

271
00:18:43,050 --> 00:18:44,680
it?

272
00:18:44,680 --> 00:18:47,670
That ship was no ship of this solar system!"

273
00:18:47,670 --> 00:18:50,870
"Where did he come from then?"

274
00:18:50,870 --> 00:19:05,530
"God only knows, but it's a long, long way
off."

275
00:19:05,530 --> 00:19:18,450
II
The IP-M-122 picked them up.

276
00:19:18,450 --> 00:19:27,910
The M-122 got out there two days later, in
response to the calls the T-247 had sent out.

277
00:19:27,910 --> 00:19:32,590
As soon as she got within ten million miles
of the little tender, she began getting Cole's

278
00:19:32,590 --> 00:19:37,930
signals, and within twelve hours had reached
the tiny thing, located it, and picked it

279
00:19:37,930 --> 00:19:38,930
up.

280
00:19:38,930 --> 00:19:43,770
Captain Jim Warren was in command, one of
the old school commanders of the IP.

281
00:19:43,770 --> 00:19:50,080
He listened to Kendall's report, listened
to Cole's tale—and radioed back a report

282
00:19:50,080 --> 00:19:51,080
of his own.

283
00:19:51,080 --> 00:19:57,490
Space pirates in a large ship had attacked
the T-247, he said, and carried it away.

284
00:19:57,490 --> 00:19:59,770
He advised a close watch.

285
00:19:59,770 --> 00:20:05,440
On Pluto, his investigations disclosed nothing
more than the fact that three mines had been

286
00:20:05,440 --> 00:20:10,610
raided, all platinum supplies taken, and the
records and machinery removed.

287
00:20:10,610 --> 00:20:17,450
The M-122 was a fifty-man patrol cruiser,
and Warren felt sure he could handle the menace

288
00:20:17,450 --> 00:20:21,170
alone, and hung around for over two weeks
looking for it.

289
00:20:21,170 --> 00:20:25,680
He saw nothing, and no further reports came
of attack.

290
00:20:25,680 --> 00:20:31,080
Again and again, Kendall tried to convince
him this ship he was hunting was no mere space

291
00:20:31,080 --> 00:20:36,670
pirate, and again and again Warren grunted,
and went on his way.

292
00:20:36,670 --> 00:20:43,080
He would not send in any report Kendall made
out, because to do so would add his endorsement

293
00:20:43,080 --> 00:20:44,780
to that report.

294
00:20:44,780 --> 00:20:50,170
He would not take Kendall back, though that
was well within his authority.

295
00:20:50,170 --> 00:20:55,790
In fact, it was a full month before Kendall
again set foot on any of the Minor Planets,

296
00:20:55,790 --> 00:21:00,110
and then it was Mars, the base of the M-122.

297
00:21:00,110 --> 00:21:04,500
Kendall and Cole took passage immediately
on an IP supply ship, and landed in New York

298
00:21:04,500 --> 00:21:06,040
six days later.

299
00:21:06,040 --> 00:21:10,510
At once, Kendall headed for Commander McLaurin's
office.

300
00:21:10,510 --> 00:21:15,560
Buck Kendall, lieutenant of the IP, found
he would have to make regular application

301
00:21:15,560 --> 00:21:20,740
to see McLaurin through a dozen intermediate
officers.

302
00:21:20,740 --> 00:21:26,130
By this time, Kendall was savagely determined
to see McLaurin himself, and see him in the

303
00:21:26,130 --> 00:21:28,140
least possible time.

304
00:21:28,140 --> 00:21:33,910
Cole, too, was beginning to believe in Kendall's
assertion of the stranger ship's extra-systemic

305
00:21:33,910 --> 00:21:35,960
origin.

306
00:21:35,960 --> 00:21:40,810
As yet neither could understand the strange
actions of the machine, its attack on the

307
00:21:40,810 --> 00:21:44,890
Pluto mines, and the capture and theft of
a patrol ship.

308
00:21:44,890 --> 00:21:52,280
"There is," said Kendall angrily, "just one
way to see McLaurin and see him quick.

309
00:21:52,280 --> 00:21:55,740
And, by God, I'm going to.

310
00:21:55,740 --> 00:21:57,730
Will you resign with me, Cole?

311
00:21:57,730 --> 00:22:01,230
I'll see him within a week then, I'll bet."

312
00:22:01,230 --> 00:22:03,610
For a minute, Cole hesitated.

313
00:22:03,610 --> 00:22:06,410
Then he shook hands with his friends.

314
00:22:06,410 --> 00:22:07,750
"Today!"

315
00:22:07,750 --> 00:22:09,740
And that day it was.

316
00:22:09,740 --> 00:22:12,030
They resigned, together.

317
00:22:12,030 --> 00:22:17,080
Immediately, Buck Kendall got the machinery
in motion for an interview, working now from

318
00:22:17,080 --> 00:22:22,920
the outside, pulling the strings with the
weight of a hundred million dollar fortune.

319
00:22:22,920 --> 00:22:28,910
Even the IP officers had to pay a bit of attention
when Bernard Kendall, multi-millionaire began

320
00:22:28,910 --> 00:22:30,750
talking and demanding things.

321
00:22:30,750 --> 00:22:36,770
Within a week, Kendall did see McLaurin.

322
00:22:36,770 --> 00:22:42,840
At that time, McLaurin was fifty-three years
old, his crisp hair still black as space,

323
00:22:42,840 --> 00:22:47,340
with scarcely a touch of the gray that appears
in his more recent photographs.

324
00:22:47,340 --> 00:22:52,520
He stood six feet tall, a broad-shouldered,
powerful man, his face grave with lines of

325
00:22:52,520 --> 00:22:54,390
intelligence and character.

326
00:22:54,390 --> 00:23:00,500
There was also a permanent narrowing of the
eyes, from years under the blazing sun of

327
00:23:00,500 --> 00:23:01,540
space.

328
00:23:01,540 --> 00:23:07,470
But most of all, while those years in space
had narrowed and set his eyes, they had not

329
00:23:07,470 --> 00:23:09,630
narrowed and set his mind.

330
00:23:09,630 --> 00:23:15,250
An infinitely finer character than old Jim
Warren, his experience in space had taught

331
00:23:15,250 --> 00:23:21,640
him always to expect the unexpected, to understand
the incomprehensible as being part of the

332
00:23:21,640 --> 00:23:27,580
unknown and incalculable properties of space
and the worlds that swam in it.

333
00:23:27,580 --> 00:23:33,500
Besides the fine technical education he had
started with, he had acquired a liberal education

334
00:23:33,500 --> 00:23:35,580
in mankind.

335
00:23:35,580 --> 00:23:40,880
When Buck Kendall, straight and powerful,
came into his office with Cole, he recognized

336
00:23:40,880 --> 00:23:44,920
in him a character that would drive steadily
and straight for its goal.

337
00:23:44,920 --> 00:23:50,520
Also, he recognized behind the millionaire
that had succeeded in pulling wires enough

338
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:57,520
to see him, the scientist who had had more
than one paper published "in an amateur way."

339
00:23:57,520 --> 00:23:59,880
"Dr. Bernard Kendall?"

340
00:23:59,880 --> 00:24:01,200
he asked, rising.

341
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:02,420
"Yes, sir.

342
00:24:02,420 --> 00:24:04,351
Late Buck Kendall, lieutenant of the IP.

343
00:24:04,351 --> 00:24:09,270
I quit and got Cole here to quit with me,
so we could see you."

344
00:24:09,270 --> 00:24:11,150
"Unusual tactics.

345
00:24:11,150 --> 00:24:14,980
I've had several men join up to get an interview
with me."

346
00:24:14,980 --> 00:24:16,670
McLaurin smiled.

347
00:24:16,670 --> 00:24:21,100
"Yes, I can imagine that, but we had to see
you in a hurry.

348
00:24:21,100 --> 00:24:27,260
A hidebound old rapscallion by the name of
Jim Warren picked us up out by Pluto, floating

349
00:24:27,260 --> 00:24:29,890
around in a six-man tender.

350
00:24:29,890 --> 00:24:34,310
We made some reports to him, but he wouldn't
believe, and he wouldn't send them through—so

351
00:24:34,310 --> 00:24:36,870
we had to send ourselves through.

352
00:24:36,870 --> 00:24:43,050
Sir, this system is about to be attacked by
some extra-systemic race.

353
00:24:43,050 --> 00:24:49,770
The IP-T-247 was so attacked, her crew killed
off, and the ship itself carried away."

354
00:24:49,770 --> 00:24:55,660
"I got the report Captain Jim Warren sent
through, stating it was a gang of space pirates.

355
00:24:55,660 --> 00:24:57,990
Now what makes you believe otherwise?"

356
00:24:57,990 --> 00:25:05,540
"That ship that attacked us, attacked with
a neutron gun, a gun that shot neutrons through

357
00:25:05,540 --> 00:25:10,270
the hull of our ship as easily as protons
pass through open space.

358
00:25:10,270 --> 00:25:15,420
Those neutrons killed off four of the crew,
and spared us only because we happened to

359
00:25:15,420 --> 00:25:17,820
be behind the water tanks.

360
00:25:17,820 --> 00:25:23,460
Masses of hydrogen will stop neutrons, so
we lived, and escaped in the tender.

361
00:25:23,460 --> 00:25:28,120
The little tender, lightless, escaped their
observation, and we were picked up.

362
00:25:28,120 --> 00:25:34,270
Now, when the 247 had been picked up, and
locked into their ship, that ship started

363
00:25:34,270 --> 00:25:35,270
accelerating.

364
00:25:35,270 --> 00:25:40,400
It accelerated so fast along my line of sight
that it just dwindled, and—vanished.

365
00:25:40,400 --> 00:25:47,440
It didn't vanish in distance, it vanished
because it exceeded the speed of light."

366
00:25:47,440 --> 00:25:49,860
"Isn't that impossible?"

367
00:25:49,860 --> 00:25:51,320
"Not at all.

368
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:57,100
It can be done—if you can find some way
of escaping from this space to do it.

369
00:25:57,100 --> 00:26:01,480
Now if you could cut across through a higher
dimension, your projection in this dimension

370
00:26:01,480 --> 00:26:04,170
might easily exceed the speed of light.

371
00:26:04,170 --> 00:26:09,010
For instance, if I could cut directly through
the Earth, at a speed of one thousand miles

372
00:26:09,010 --> 00:26:14,120
an hour, my projection on the surface would
go twelve thousand miles while I was going

373
00:26:14,120 --> 00:26:15,140
eight.

374
00:26:15,140 --> 00:26:19,900
Similar, if you could cut through the four
dimensional space instead of following its

375
00:26:19,900 --> 00:26:22,850
surface, you'd attain a speed greater than
light."

376
00:26:22,850 --> 00:26:26,750
"Might it not still be a space pirate?

377
00:26:26,750 --> 00:26:30,840
That's a lot easier to believe, even allowing
your statement that he exceeded the speed

378
00:26:30,840 --> 00:26:31,840
of light."

379
00:26:31,840 --> 00:26:37,760
"If you invented a neutron gun which could
kill through tungsten walls without injuring

380
00:26:37,760 --> 00:26:42,950
anything within, a system of accelerating
a ship that didn't affect the inhabitants

381
00:26:42,950 --> 00:26:47,500
of that ship, and a means of exceeding the
speed of light, all within a few months of

382
00:26:47,500 --> 00:26:50,660
each other, would you become a pirate?

383
00:26:50,660 --> 00:26:54,000
I wouldn't, and I don't think any one else
would.

384
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:57,400
A pirate is a man who seeks adventure and
relief from work.

385
00:26:57,400 --> 00:27:02,780
Given a means of exceeding the speed of light,
I'd get all the adventure I wanted investigating

386
00:27:02,780 --> 00:27:03,980
other planets.

387
00:27:03,980 --> 00:27:09,570
If I didn't have a cent before, I'd have relief
from work by selling it for a few hundred

388
00:27:09,570 --> 00:27:16,400
millions—and I'd sell it mighty easily too,
for an invention like that is worth an incalculable

389
00:27:16,400 --> 00:27:17,400
sum.

390
00:27:17,400 --> 00:27:23,110
Tie to that the value of compensated acceleration,
and no man's going to turn pirate.

391
00:27:23,110 --> 00:27:27,860
He can make more millions selling his inventions
than he can make thousands turning pirate

392
00:27:27,860 --> 00:27:28,860
with them.

393
00:27:28,860 --> 00:27:31,230
So who'd turn pirate?"

394
00:27:31,230 --> 00:27:33,040
"Right."

395
00:27:33,040 --> 00:27:34,040
McLaurin nodded.

396
00:27:34,040 --> 00:27:35,970
"I see your point.

397
00:27:35,970 --> 00:27:41,910
Now before I'd accept your statements in re
the 'speed of light' thing, I'd want opinions

398
00:27:41,910 --> 00:27:43,490
from some IP physicists."

399
00:27:43,490 --> 00:27:47,820
"Then let's have a conference, because something's
got to be done soon.

400
00:27:47,820 --> 00:27:51,040
I don't know why we haven't heard further
from that fellow."

401
00:27:51,040 --> 00:27:56,450
"Privately—we have," McLaurin said in a
slightly worried tone.

402
00:27:56,450 --> 00:28:02,580
"He was detected by the instruments of every
IP observatory I suspect.

403
00:28:02,580 --> 00:28:05,760
We got the reports but didn't know what to
make of them.

404
00:28:05,760 --> 00:28:11,010
They indicated so many funny things, they
were sent in as accidental misreadings of

405
00:28:11,010 --> 00:28:12,130
the instruments.

406
00:28:12,130 --> 00:28:17,570
But since all the observatories reported them,
similar misreadings, at about the same times,

407
00:28:17,570 --> 00:28:23,400
that is with variations of only a few hours,
we thought something must have been up.

408
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:28,841
The only thing was the phenomena were reported
progressively from Pluto to Neptune, clear

409
00:28:28,841 --> 00:28:34,720
across the solar system, in a definite progression,
but at a velocity of crossing that didn't

410
00:28:34,720 --> 00:28:37,110
tie in with any conceivable force.

411
00:28:37,110 --> 00:28:40,320
They crossed faster than the velocity of light.

412
00:28:40,320 --> 00:28:46,190
That ship must have spent about half an hour
off each planet before passing on to the next.

413
00:28:46,190 --> 00:28:51,430
And, accepting your faster-than-light explanation,
we can understand it."

414
00:28:51,430 --> 00:28:53,280
"Then I think you have proof."

415
00:28:53,280 --> 00:28:56,900
"If we have, what would you do about it?"

416
00:28:56,900 --> 00:29:02,470
"Get to work on those 'misreadings' of the
instruments for one thing, and for a second,

417
00:29:02,470 --> 00:29:07,220
and more important, line every IP ship with
paraffin blocks six inches thick."

418
00:29:07,220 --> 00:29:09,250
"Paraffin—why?"

419
00:29:09,250 --> 00:29:13,760
"The easiest form of hydrogen to get.

420
00:29:13,760 --> 00:29:17,510
You can't use solid hydrogen, because that
melts too easily.

421
00:29:17,510 --> 00:29:21,690
Water can be turned into steam too easily,
and requires more work.

422
00:29:21,690 --> 00:29:24,470
Paraffin is a solid that's largely hydrogen.

423
00:29:24,470 --> 00:29:28,890
That's what they've always used on neutrons
since they discovered them.

424
00:29:28,890 --> 00:29:33,430
Confine your paraffin between tungsten walls,
and you'll stop the secondary protons as well

425
00:29:33,430 --> 00:29:35,290
as the neutrons."

426
00:29:35,290 --> 00:29:37,640
"Hmmm—I suppose so.

427
00:29:37,640 --> 00:29:39,960
How about seeing those physicists?"

428
00:29:39,960 --> 00:29:43,150
"I'd like to see them today, sir.

429
00:29:43,150 --> 00:29:46,840
The sooner you get started on this work, the
better it will be for the IP."

430
00:29:46,840 --> 00:29:51,410
"Having seen me, will you join up in the IP
again?" asked McLaurin.

431
00:29:51,410 --> 00:29:53,510
"No, sir, I don't think I will.

432
00:29:53,510 --> 00:29:58,180
I have another field you know, in which I
may be more useful.

433
00:29:58,180 --> 00:30:03,030
Cole here's a better technician than fighter—and
a darned good fighter, too—and I think that

434
00:30:03,030 --> 00:30:07,590
an inexperienced space-captain is a lot less
useful than a second-rate physicist at work

435
00:30:07,590 --> 00:30:08,730
in a laboratory.

436
00:30:08,730 --> 00:30:14,310
If we hope to get anywhere, or for that matter,
I suspect, stay anywhere, we'll have to do

437
00:30:14,310 --> 00:30:16,520
a lot of research pretty promptly."

438
00:30:16,520 --> 00:30:19,280
"What's your explanation of that ship?"

439
00:30:19,280 --> 00:30:28,060
"One of two things: an inventor of some other
system trying out his latest toy, or an expedition

440
00:30:28,060 --> 00:30:30,960
sent out by a planetary government for exploration.

441
00:30:30,960 --> 00:30:36,510
I favor the latter for two reasons: that ship
was big.

442
00:30:36,510 --> 00:30:41,080
No inventor would build a thing that size,
requiring a crew of several hundred men to

443
00:30:41,080 --> 00:30:43,120
try out his invention.

444
00:30:43,120 --> 00:30:49,020
A government would build just about that if
they wanted to send out an expedition.

445
00:30:49,020 --> 00:30:52,820
If it were an inventor, he'd be interested
in meeting other people, to see what they

446
00:30:52,820 --> 00:30:59,090
had in the way of science, and probably he'd
want to do it in a peaceable way.

447
00:30:59,090 --> 00:31:02,440
That fellow wasn't interested in peace, by
any means.

448
00:31:02,440 --> 00:31:07,330
So I think it's a government ship, and an
unfriendly government.

449
00:31:07,330 --> 00:31:13,460
They sent that ship out either for scientific
research, for trade research and exploration,

450
00:31:13,460 --> 00:31:15,620
or for acquisitive exploration.

451
00:31:15,620 --> 00:31:20,680
If they were out for scientific research,
they'd proceed as would the inventor, to establish

452
00:31:20,680 --> 00:31:22,580
friendly communication.

453
00:31:22,580 --> 00:31:25,490
If they were out for trade, the same would
apply.

454
00:31:25,490 --> 00:31:32,411
If they were out for acquisitive exploration,
they'd investigate the planets, the sun, the

455
00:31:32,411 --> 00:31:36,700
people, only to the extent of learning how
best to overcome them.

456
00:31:36,700 --> 00:31:40,260
They'd want to get a sample of our people,
and a sample of our weapons.

457
00:31:40,260 --> 00:31:45,370
They'd want samples of our machinery, our
literature and our technology.

458
00:31:45,370 --> 00:31:48,800
That's exactly what that ship got.

459
00:31:48,800 --> 00:31:56,270
"Somebody, somewhere out there in space, either
doesn't like their home, or wants more home.

460
00:31:56,270 --> 00:31:58,400
They've been out looking for one.

461
00:31:58,400 --> 00:32:04,010
I'll bet they sent out hundreds of expeditions
to thousands of nearby stars, gradually going

462
00:32:04,010 --> 00:32:07,300
further and further, seeking a planetary system.

463
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:10,160
This is probably the one and only one they
found.

464
00:32:10,160 --> 00:32:11,690
It's a good one too.

465
00:32:11,690 --> 00:32:14,900
It has planets at all temperatures, of all
sizes.

466
00:32:14,900 --> 00:32:20,190
It is a fairly compact one, it has a stable
sun that will last far longer than any race

467
00:32:20,190 --> 00:32:21,520
can hope to."

468
00:32:21,520 --> 00:32:28,100
"Hmm—how can there be good and bad planetary
systems?" asked McLaurin.

469
00:32:28,100 --> 00:32:31,180
"I'd never thought of that."

470
00:32:31,180 --> 00:32:32,180
Kendall laughed.

471
00:32:32,180 --> 00:32:33,180
"Mighty easy.

472
00:32:33,180 --> 00:32:37,120
How'd you like to live on a planet of a Cepheid
Variable?

473
00:32:37,120 --> 00:32:42,340
Pleasant situation, with the radiation flaring
up and down.

474
00:32:42,340 --> 00:32:44,640
How'd you like to live on a planet of Antares?

475
00:32:44,640 --> 00:32:50,050
That blasted sun is so big, to have a comfortable
planet you'd have to be at least ten billion

476
00:32:50,050 --> 00:32:51,710
miles out.

477
00:32:51,710 --> 00:32:56,180
Then if you had an interplanetary commerce,
you'd have to struggle with orbits tens of

478
00:32:56,180 --> 00:32:59,980
billions of miles across instead of mere millions.

479
00:32:59,980 --> 00:33:06,310
Further, you'd have a sun so blasted big,
it would take an impossible amount of energy

480
00:33:06,310 --> 00:33:09,250
to lift the ship up from one planet to another.

481
00:33:09,250 --> 00:33:14,900
If your trip was, say, twenty billions of
miles to the next planet, you'd be fighting

482
00:33:14,900 --> 00:33:20,450
a gravity as bad as the solar gravity at Earth
here all the way—no decline with a little

483
00:33:20,450 --> 00:33:22,720
distance like that."

484
00:33:22,720 --> 00:33:25,810
"H-m-m-m—quite true.

485
00:33:25,810 --> 00:33:29,580
Then I should say that Mira would take the
prize.

486
00:33:29,580 --> 00:33:33,240
It's a red giant, and it's an irregular variable.

487
00:33:33,240 --> 00:33:37,680
The sunlight there would be as unstable as
the weather in New England.

488
00:33:37,680 --> 00:33:41,440
It's almost as big as Antares, and it won't
hold still.

489
00:33:41,440 --> 00:33:45,270
Now that would make a bad planetary system."

490
00:33:45,270 --> 00:33:47,290
"It would!"

491
00:33:47,290 --> 00:33:48,290
Kendall laughed.

492
00:33:48,290 --> 00:34:06,310
But as we know—he laughed too soon, and
he shouldn't have used 

493
00:34:06,310 --> 00:34:07,500
the conditional.

494
00:34:07,500 --> 00:34:14,629
He should have said, "It does!"

495
00:34:14,629 --> 00:34:19,169
III
Gresth Gkae, Commander of Expeditionary Force

496
00:34:19,169 --> 00:34:25,380
93, of the Planet Sthor, was returning homeward
with joyful mind.

497
00:34:25,380 --> 00:34:29,379
In the lock of his great ship, lay the T-247.

498
00:34:29,379 --> 00:34:36,040
In her cargo holds lay various items of machinery,
mining supplies, foods, and records.

499
00:34:36,040 --> 00:34:41,149
And in her log books lay the records of many
readings on the nine larger planets of a highly

500
00:34:41,149 --> 00:34:45,050
satisfactory planetary system.

501
00:34:45,050 --> 00:34:52,679
Gresth Gkae had spent no less than three ultra-wearing
years going from one sun to another in a definitely

502
00:34:52,679 --> 00:34:55,220
mapped out section of space.

503
00:34:55,220 --> 00:35:00,880
He had investigated only eleven stars in that
time, eleven stars, progressively further

504
00:35:00,880 --> 00:35:05,950
from the titanic red-flaming sun he knew as
"the" sun.

505
00:35:05,950 --> 00:35:12,019
He knew it as "the" sun, and had several other
appellations for it.

506
00:35:12,019 --> 00:35:19,430
Mira was so-named by Earthmen because it was
indeed a "wonder" star, in Latin, mirare means

507
00:35:19,430 --> 00:35:20,849
"to wonder."

508
00:35:20,849 --> 00:35:25,930
Irregularly, and for no apparent reason it
would change its rate of radiation.

509
00:35:25,930 --> 00:35:32,740
So far as those inhabitants of Sthor and her
sister world Asthor knew, there was no reason.

510
00:35:32,740 --> 00:35:35,400
It just did it.

511
00:35:35,400 --> 00:35:37,650
Perhaps with malicious intent to be annoying.

512
00:35:37,650 --> 00:35:41,690
If so, it was exceptionally successful.

513
00:35:41,690 --> 00:35:47,859
Sthor and Asthor experienced, periodically,
a young ice age.

514
00:35:47,859 --> 00:35:53,990
When Mira decided to take a rest, Sthor and
Asthor froze up, from the poles most of the

515
00:35:53,990 --> 00:35:56,070
way to the equators.

516
00:35:56,070 --> 00:36:01,210
Then Mira would stretch herself a little,
move about restlessly and Sthor and Asthor

517
00:36:01,210 --> 00:36:07,470
would become uninhabitably hot, anywhere within
twenty degrees of the equator.

518
00:36:07,470 --> 00:36:12,150
Those Sthorian people had evolved in a way
that made the conditions endurable for savage

519
00:36:12,150 --> 00:36:18,269
or uncivilized people, but when a scientific
civilization with a well-ordered mode of existence

520
00:36:18,269 --> 00:36:24,249
tried to establish itself, Mira was all sorts
of a nuisance.

521
00:36:24,249 --> 00:36:29,510
Gresth Gkae was a peculiar individual to human
ways of thinking.

522
00:36:29,510 --> 00:36:35,470
He stood some seven feet tall, on his strange,
double-kneed legs and his four toed feet.

523
00:36:35,470 --> 00:36:40,520
His body was covered with little, short feather-like
things that moved now with a volition of their

524
00:36:40,520 --> 00:36:41,999
own.

525
00:36:41,999 --> 00:36:45,369
They were moving very slowly and regularly.

526
00:36:45,369 --> 00:36:49,970
The space-ship was heated to a comfortable
temperature, and the little fans were helping

527
00:36:49,970 --> 00:36:52,450
to cool Gresth Gkae.

528
00:36:52,450 --> 00:36:57,650
Had it been cold, every little feather would
have lain down close against its neighbors,

529
00:36:57,650 --> 00:37:00,950
forming an admirable, wind-proof and cold-proof
blanket.

530
00:37:00,950 --> 00:37:06,519
Nature, on Sthor, had original ideas of arrangement
too.

531
00:37:06,519 --> 00:37:13,450
Sthorians possessed two eyes—one directly
above the other, in the center of their faces.

532
00:37:13,450 --> 00:37:18,519
The face was so long, and narrow, it resembled
a blunt hatchet, with the two eyes on the

533
00:37:18,519 --> 00:37:19,869
edge.

534
00:37:19,869 --> 00:37:24,450
To counter-balance this vertical arrangement
of the eyes, the nostrils had been separated

535
00:37:24,450 --> 00:37:29,160
some four inches, with one on each of the
sloping cheeks.

536
00:37:29,160 --> 00:37:33,259
His ears were little pink-flesh cups on short,
muscular stems.

537
00:37:33,259 --> 00:37:39,549
His mouth was narrow, and small, but armed
with quite solid teeth adapted to his diet,

538
00:37:39,549 --> 00:37:45,920
a diet consisting of almost anything any creature
had ever considered edible.

539
00:37:45,920 --> 00:37:51,510
Like most successful forms of intelligent
life, Gresth Gkae was omnivorous.

540
00:37:51,510 --> 00:37:56,869
An intelligent form of life is necessarily
adaptable, and adaptation meant being able

541
00:37:56,869 --> 00:38:00,009
to eat what was at hand.

542
00:38:00,009 --> 00:38:04,789
One of his eyes, the upper one, was fully
twice the size of the lower one.

543
00:38:04,789 --> 00:38:06,700
This was his telescopic eye.

544
00:38:06,700 --> 00:38:12,839
The lower, or microscopic eye was adapted
to work for which a human being would have

545
00:38:12,839 --> 00:38:18,170
required a low power microscope, the upper
eye possessed a more normal power of vision,

546
00:38:18,170 --> 00:38:21,950
plus considerable telescopic powers.

547
00:38:21,950 --> 00:38:27,480
Gresth Gkae was using it now to look ahead
in the blank of space to where gigantic Mira

548
00:38:27,480 --> 00:38:29,050
appeared.

549
00:38:29,050 --> 00:38:34,500
On his screens now, Mira appeared deep violet,
for he was approaching at a speed greater

550
00:38:34,500 --> 00:38:39,569
than that of light, and even this projected
light of Mira was badly distorted.

551
00:38:39,569 --> 00:38:44,359
"The distance is half a light-year now, sir,"
reported the navigation officer.

552
00:38:44,359 --> 00:38:48,250
"Reduce the speed, then, to normal velocity
for these ranges.

553
00:38:48,250 --> 00:38:49,999
What reserve of fuel have we?"

554
00:38:49,999 --> 00:38:51,779
"Less than one thousand pounds.

555
00:38:51,779 --> 00:38:54,410
We will barely be able to stop.

556
00:38:54,410 --> 00:38:58,599
We were too free in the use of our weapons,
I fear," replied the Chief Technician.

557
00:38:58,599 --> 00:39:00,809
"Well, what would you?

558
00:39:00,809 --> 00:39:03,220
We needed those things in our reports.

559
00:39:03,220 --> 00:39:09,410
Besides, we could extract fuel from that ore
we took on at Planet Nine of Phahlo.

560
00:39:09,410 --> 00:39:12,480
It is merely that I wish speed in the return."

561
00:39:12,480 --> 00:39:15,430
"As we all do.

562
00:39:15,430 --> 00:39:19,049
How soon do you believe the Council will proceed
against the new system?"

563
00:39:19,049 --> 00:39:22,140
"It will be fully a year, I fear.

564
00:39:22,140 --> 00:39:26,349
They must gather the expeditions together,
and re-equip the ships.

565
00:39:26,349 --> 00:39:28,740
It will be a long time before all will have
come in."

566
00:39:28,740 --> 00:39:33,220
"Could they not send fast ships after them
to recall them?"

567
00:39:33,220 --> 00:39:39,269
"Could they have traced us as we wove our
way from Thart to Karst to Raloork to Phahlo?

568
00:39:39,269 --> 00:39:42,510
It would be impossible."

569
00:39:42,510 --> 00:39:45,950
Steadily the great ship had been boring on
her way.

570
00:39:45,950 --> 00:39:52,230
Mira had been a disc for nearly two days,
gigantic, two-hundred-and-fifty-million-mile

571
00:39:52,230 --> 00:39:57,240
Mira took a great deal of dwarfing by distance
to lose her disc.

572
00:39:57,240 --> 00:40:02,099
Even at the Twin Planets, eight thousand two
hundred and fifty millions of miles out, Mira

573
00:40:02,099 --> 00:40:06,020
covered half the sky, it seemed, red and angry.

574
00:40:06,020 --> 00:40:12,900
Sometimes, though, to the disgust of the Sthorians
it was just red-faced and lazy.

575
00:40:12,900 --> 00:40:14,759
Then Sthor froze.

576
00:40:14,759 --> 00:40:21,369
"Grih is in a descendant stage," said the
navigation officer presently.

577
00:40:21,369 --> 00:40:23,540
"Sthor will be cold when we arrive."

578
00:40:23,540 --> 00:40:27,380
"It will warm quickly enough with our news!"

579
00:40:27,380 --> 00:40:28,380
Gresth laughed.

580
00:40:28,380 --> 00:40:30,400
"A system—a delightful system—discovered.

581
00:40:30,400 --> 00:40:36,150
A system of many close-grouped planets.

582
00:40:36,150 --> 00:40:41,569
Why think—from one side of that system to
the other is less of a distance than from

583
00:40:41,569 --> 00:40:45,799
Ansthat, our first planet's orbit, to Insthor's
orbit!

584
00:40:45,799 --> 00:40:49,119
That sun, as we know, is steady and warm.

585
00:40:49,119 --> 00:40:53,210
All will be well, when we have eliminated
that rather peculiar race.

586
00:40:53,210 --> 00:40:57,559
Odd, that they should, in some ways, be so
nearly like us!

587
00:40:57,559 --> 00:40:59,660
Nearly Sthorian in build.

588
00:40:59,660 --> 00:41:01,989
I would not have expected it.

589
00:41:01,989 --> 00:41:05,170
Though they did have some amazing peculiarities!

590
00:41:05,170 --> 00:41:10,880
Imagine—two eyes just alike, and in a horizontal
row.

591
00:41:10,880 --> 00:41:12,920
And that flat face.

592
00:41:12,920 --> 00:41:16,460
They looked as though they had suffered some
accident that smashed the front of the face

593
00:41:16,460 --> 00:41:17,460
in.

594
00:41:17,460 --> 00:41:20,079
And also the peculiar beak-like projection.

595
00:41:20,079 --> 00:41:26,150
Why should a race ever develop so amazing
a projection in so peculiar and exposed a

596
00:41:26,150 --> 00:41:27,380
position?

597
00:41:27,380 --> 00:41:29,980
It sticks out inviting attack and injury.

598
00:41:29,980 --> 00:41:32,359
Right in the middle of the face.

599
00:41:32,359 --> 00:41:37,530
And to make it worse, there is the air-channel,
and the only air channel.

600
00:41:37,530 --> 00:41:43,140
Why, one minor injury to the throat would
be certain to damage that passage beyond repair,

601
00:41:43,140 --> 00:41:44,470
and bring death.

602
00:41:44,470 --> 00:41:49,660
Yet such relatively unimportant things as
ears, and eyes are doubled.

603
00:41:49,660 --> 00:41:54,089
Surely you would expect that so important
a member as the air-passage would be doubled

604
00:41:54,089 --> 00:41:55,089
for safety.

605
00:41:55,089 --> 00:41:59,749
"Those strange, awkward arms and legs were
what puzzled me.

606
00:41:59,749 --> 00:42:04,910
I have been attempting to manipulate myself
as they must be forced to, and I cannot see

607
00:42:04,910 --> 00:42:10,289
how delicate or accurate manual manipulation
would be possible with those rigid, inflexible

608
00:42:10,289 --> 00:42:11,289
arms.

609
00:42:11,289 --> 00:42:16,989
In some ways I feel they must have had clever
minds to overcome so great a handicap to constructive

610
00:42:16,989 --> 00:42:17,989
work.

611
00:42:17,989 --> 00:42:22,940
But I suppose single joints in the arms become
as natural to them as our own more mobile

612
00:42:22,940 --> 00:42:24,130
two.

613
00:42:24,130 --> 00:42:29,500
"I wonder if life in any intelligent form
wouldn't develop somewhat similar formations,

614
00:42:29,500 --> 00:42:30,500
though.

615
00:42:30,500 --> 00:42:36,940
Think, in all parts of Sthor, before men became
civilized and developed communication, even

616
00:42:36,940 --> 00:42:42,309
so much as twenty thousand years ago, our
records show that seats and chairs were much

617
00:42:42,309 --> 00:42:47,119
as they are today, and much as they are, in
all places among all groups.

618
00:42:47,119 --> 00:42:52,640
Then too, the eye has developed in many different
species, and always reached much the same

619
00:42:52,640 --> 00:42:53,640
structure.

620
00:42:53,640 --> 00:42:58,799
When a thing is intended and developed to
serve a given purpose, no matter who develops

621
00:42:58,799 --> 00:43:03,980
it, or where or how, is it not apt to have
similar shapes and parts?

622
00:43:03,980 --> 00:43:08,609
A chair must have legs, and a seat and arm-rests
and a back.

623
00:43:08,609 --> 00:43:13,569
You may vary their nature and their shape,
but not widely, and they must be there.

624
00:43:13,569 --> 00:43:19,960
An eye must, anywhere, have a sensitive retina,
an adjustable lens, and an adjustable device

625
00:43:19,960 --> 00:43:22,830
for controlling the entrance of light.

626
00:43:22,830 --> 00:43:27,019
Similarly there are certain functions that
the body of an intelligent creature must serve

627
00:43:27,019 --> 00:43:30,529
which naturally tend to make intelligent creatures
similar.

628
00:43:30,529 --> 00:43:33,510
He must have a tool—the hand—"

629
00:43:33,510 --> 00:43:36,160
"Yes, yes—I see your point.

630
00:43:36,160 --> 00:43:41,130
It must be so, for surely these creatures
out there are strange enough in other ways."

631
00:43:41,130 --> 00:43:45,170
"But tell me, have you calculated when we
shall land?"

632
00:43:45,170 --> 00:43:50,109
"In twelve hours, thirty-three minutes, sir."

633
00:43:50,109 --> 00:43:53,809
Eleven hours later, the expedition ship had
slowed to a normal space-speed.

634
00:43:53,809 --> 00:44:02,559
On her left hung the giant globe of Asthor,
rotating slowly, moving slowly in her orbit.

635
00:44:02,559 --> 00:44:05,450
Directly ahead, Sthor loomed even greater.

636
00:44:05,450 --> 00:44:12,230
Tiny Teelan, the thousand-mile diameter moon
of the Insthor system shone dull red in the

637
00:44:12,230 --> 00:44:15,540
reflected light of gigantic Mira.

638
00:44:15,540 --> 00:44:20,849
Mira herself was gigantic, red and menacing
across eight and a quarter billions of miles

639
00:44:20,849 --> 00:44:23,559
of space.

640
00:44:23,559 --> 00:44:29,249
One hundred thousand miles apart, the twin
worlds Sthor and Asthor rotated about their

641
00:44:29,249 --> 00:44:34,130
common center of gravity, eternally facing
each other.

642
00:44:34,130 --> 00:44:40,520
Ten million miles from their common center
of gravity, Teelan rotated in a vast orbit.

643
00:44:40,520 --> 00:44:46,880
Sthor and Asthor were capped at each pole
now by gigantic white icecaps.

644
00:44:46,880 --> 00:44:51,980
Mira was sulking, and as a consequence the
planets were freezing.

645
00:44:51,980 --> 00:44:55,339
The expedition ship sank slowly toward Sthor.

646
00:44:55,339 --> 00:44:59,980
A swarm of smaller craft had flown up at its
approach to meet it.

647
00:44:59,980 --> 00:45:03,130
A gaily-colored small ship marked the official
greeting-ship.

648
00:45:03,130 --> 00:45:07,730
Gresth had withheld his news purposely.

649
00:45:07,730 --> 00:45:13,109
Now suddenly he began broadcasting it from
the powerful transmitter on his ship.

650
00:45:13,109 --> 00:45:18,221
As the words came through on a thousand sets,
all the little ships began to whirl, dance

651
00:45:18,221 --> 00:45:21,550
and break out into glowing, sparkling lights.

652
00:45:21,550 --> 00:45:26,569
On Sthor and Asthor even commotions began
to be visible.

653
00:45:26,569 --> 00:45:31,690
A new planetary system had been found— They
could move!

654
00:45:31,690 --> 00:45:35,190
Their overflowing populations could be spread
out!

655
00:45:35,190 --> 00:45:51,440
The whole Insthor system went mad with delight
as the great Expeditionary Ship settled downward.

656
00:45:51,440 --> 00:46:03,470
IV
There was a glint of humor in Buck Kendall's

657
00:46:03,470 --> 00:46:07,530
eyes as he passed the sheet over to McLaurin.

658
00:46:07,530 --> 00:46:11,599
Commander McLaurin looked down the columns
with twinkling eyes.

659
00:46:11,599 --> 00:46:16,599
"'Petition to establish the Lunar Mining Bank,'"
he read.

660
00:46:16,599 --> 00:46:18,270
"What a bank!

661
00:46:18,270 --> 00:46:24,539
Officers: President, General James Logan,
late of the IP; Vice-president, Colonel Warren

662
00:46:24,539 --> 00:46:33,290
Gerardhi, also late of the IP; Staff, consists
of 90% ex-IP men, and a few scattered accountants.

663
00:46:33,290 --> 00:46:38,480
Designed by the well-known designer of IP
stations, Colonel Richard Murray."

664
00:46:38,480 --> 00:46:41,859
Commander McLaurin looked up at Kendall with
a broad grin.

665
00:46:41,859 --> 00:46:47,410
"And you actually got Interplanetary Life
to give you a mortgage on the structure?"

666
00:46:47,410 --> 00:46:48,569
"Why not?

667
00:46:48,569 --> 00:46:53,740
It'll cut cost fifty-eight millions, with
its twelve-foot tungsten-beryllium walls and

668
00:46:53,740 --> 00:46:57,039
the heavy defense weapons against those terrible
pirates.

669
00:46:57,039 --> 00:46:58,829
You know we must defend our property."

670
00:46:58,829 --> 00:47:04,299
"With the thing you're setting up out there
on Luna, you could more readily wipe out the

671
00:47:04,299 --> 00:47:06,980
IP than anything else I know of.

672
00:47:06,980 --> 00:47:08,829
Any new defense ideas?"

673
00:47:08,829 --> 00:47:09,829
"Plenty.

674
00:47:09,829 --> 00:47:14,450
Did you get any further appropriations from
the IP Appropriations Board?"

675
00:47:14,450 --> 00:47:16,970
McLaurin looked sour.

676
00:47:16,970 --> 00:47:17,970
"No.

677
00:47:17,970 --> 00:47:23,210
The dear taxpayers might object, and those
thickheaded, clogged rockets on the Board

678
00:47:23,210 --> 00:47:26,230
can't see your data on the Stranger.

679
00:47:26,230 --> 00:47:30,890
They gave me just ten millions, and that only
because you demonstrated you could shoot every

680
00:47:30,890 --> 00:47:35,380
living thing out of the latest IP cruiser
with that neutron gun of yours.

681
00:47:35,380 --> 00:47:39,609
By the way, they may kick when I don't install
more than a few of those."

682
00:47:39,609 --> 00:47:41,220
"Let 'em.

683
00:47:41,220 --> 00:47:43,339
You can stall for a few months.

684
00:47:43,339 --> 00:47:45,880
You'll need that money more for other purposes.

685
00:47:45,880 --> 00:47:47,799
You've installed that paraffin lining?"

686
00:47:47,799 --> 00:47:51,480
"Yes—I got a report on that of 'finished'
last week.

687
00:47:51,480 --> 00:47:53,820
How have you made out?"

688
00:47:53,820 --> 00:47:55,650
Buck Kendall's face fell.

689
00:47:55,650 --> 00:47:57,440
"Not so hot.

690
00:47:57,440 --> 00:48:02,040
Devin's been the biggest help—he did most
of the work on that neutron gun really—"

691
00:48:02,040 --> 00:48:05,630
"After," McLaurin interrupted, "you told him
how."

692
00:48:05,630 --> 00:48:08,109
"—but we're pretty well stuck now, it seems.

693
00:48:08,109 --> 00:48:12,049
You'll be off duty tomorrow evening, can't
you drop around to the lab?

694
00:48:12,049 --> 00:48:16,430
We're going to try out a new system for releasing
atomic energy."

695
00:48:16,430 --> 00:48:19,400
"Isn't that a pretty faint hope?

696
00:48:19,400 --> 00:48:22,510
We've been trying to get it for three centuries
now, and haven't yet.

697
00:48:22,510 --> 00:48:27,220
What chance at it within a year or so?—which
is the time you allow yourself before the

698
00:48:27,220 --> 00:48:28,700
Stranger returns."

699
00:48:28,700 --> 00:48:31,940
"It is, I'll admit that.

700
00:48:31,940 --> 00:48:35,490
But there's another factor, not to be forgotten.

701
00:48:35,490 --> 00:48:43,440
The data we got from correlating those 'misreadings'
from the various IP posts mean a lot.

702
00:48:43,440 --> 00:48:47,119
We are working on an entirely different trail
now.

703
00:48:47,119 --> 00:48:50,150
You come on out, and you can see our new apparatus.

704
00:48:50,150 --> 00:48:54,920
They are working on tremendous voltages, and
hoping to smash the thing by a brutal bombardment

705
00:48:54,920 --> 00:48:56,339
of terrific voltage.

706
00:48:56,339 --> 00:49:02,160
We're trying, thanks to the results of those
instruments, to get results with small, terrifically

707
00:49:02,160 --> 00:49:04,099
intense fields."

708
00:49:04,099 --> 00:49:07,319
"How do you know that's their general system?"

709
00:49:07,319 --> 00:49:10,839
"They left traces on the records of the post
instruments.

710
00:49:10,839 --> 00:49:14,800
These records show such intensities as we
never got.

711
00:49:14,800 --> 00:49:21,239
They have atomic energy, necessarily, and
they might have had material energy, actual

712
00:49:21,239 --> 00:49:25,640
destruction of matter, but apparently, from
the field readings it's the former.

713
00:49:25,640 --> 00:49:30,769
To be able to make those tremendous hops,
light-years in length, they needed a real

714
00:49:30,769 --> 00:49:32,229
store of energy.

715
00:49:32,229 --> 00:49:37,150
They have accumulators, of course, but I don't
think they could store enough power by the

716
00:49:37,150 --> 00:49:39,400
system they use to do it."

717
00:49:39,400 --> 00:49:45,039
"Well, how's your trick 'bank' out on Luna,
despite its twelve-foot walls, going to stand

718
00:49:45,039 --> 00:49:46,829
an atomic explosion?"

719
00:49:46,829 --> 00:49:50,529
"More protective devices to come is our only
hope.

720
00:49:50,529 --> 00:49:56,619
I'm working on three trails: atomic energy,
some type of magnetic shield that will stop

721
00:49:56,619 --> 00:50:00,900
any moving material particle, and their faster-than-light
thing.

722
00:50:00,900 --> 00:50:06,549
Also, that fortress—I mean, of course, bank—is
going to have a lot of lead-lined rooms."

723
00:50:06,549 --> 00:50:12,150
"I wish I could use the remaining money the
Board gave me to lead-line a lot of those

724
00:50:12,150 --> 00:50:14,799
IP ships," said McLaurin wistfully.

725
00:50:14,799 --> 00:50:18,269
"Can't you make a gamma-ray bomb of some sort?"

726
00:50:18,269 --> 00:50:20,930
"Not without their atomic energy release.

727
00:50:20,930 --> 00:50:24,710
With it, of course, it's easy to flood a region
with rays.

728
00:50:24,710 --> 00:50:28,109
It'll be a million times worse than radium
'C,' which is bad enough."

729
00:50:28,109 --> 00:50:32,200
"Well, I'll send through this petition for
armaments.

730
00:50:32,200 --> 00:50:34,519
They'll pass it all right, I think.

731
00:50:34,519 --> 00:50:38,369
They may get some kicks from old Jacob Ezra
Stubbs.

732
00:50:38,369 --> 00:50:41,229
Jacob Ezra doesn't believe in anything war-like.

733
00:50:41,229 --> 00:50:46,299
I wish they'd find some way to keep him off
of the Arms Petition Board.

734
00:50:46,299 --> 00:50:50,749
He might just as well stay home and let 'em
vote his ticket uniformly 'nay.'"

735
00:50:50,749 --> 00:50:54,569
Buck Kendall left with a laugh.

736
00:50:54,569 --> 00:50:56,800
Buck Kendall had his troubles though.

737
00:50:56,800 --> 00:51:01,069
When he had reached Earth again, he found
that his properties totaled one hundred and

738
00:51:01,069 --> 00:51:03,769
three million dollars, roughly.

739
00:51:03,769 --> 00:51:08,380
One doesn't sell properties of that magnitude,
one borrows against them.

740
00:51:08,380 --> 00:51:14,130
But to all intents and purposes, Buck Kendall
owned two half-completed ship's hulls in the

741
00:51:14,130 --> 00:51:20,309
Baldwin Spaceship Yards, a great deal of massive
metal work on its way to Luna, and contracts

742
00:51:20,309 --> 00:51:23,980
for some very extensive work on a "bank."

743
00:51:23,980 --> 00:51:27,450
Beyond that, about eleven million was left.

744
00:51:27,450 --> 00:51:32,869
A large portion of the money had been invested
in a laboratory, the like of which the world

745
00:51:32,869 --> 00:51:34,030
had never seen.

746
00:51:34,030 --> 00:51:39,880
It was devoted exclusively to physics, and
principally the physics of destruction.

747
00:51:39,880 --> 00:51:46,049
Dr. Paul Devin was the Director, Cole was
in charge of the technical work, and Buck

748
00:51:46,049 --> 00:51:49,250
Kendall was free to do all the work he thought
needed doing.

749
00:51:49,250 --> 00:51:54,400
Returned to his laboratory, he looked sourly
at the bench on which seven mechanicians were

750
00:51:54,400 --> 00:51:55,599
working.

751
00:51:55,599 --> 00:52:00,390
The ninth successive experiment on the release
of atomic energy had failed.

752
00:52:00,390 --> 00:52:02,789
The tenth was in process of construction.

753
00:52:02,789 --> 00:52:08,609
A heavy pure tungsten dome, three feet in
diameter, three inches thick, was being lowered

754
00:52:08,609 --> 00:52:12,069
over a clear insulum dome, a foot smaller.

755
00:52:12,069 --> 00:52:16,979
Inside, the real apparatus was arranged around
the little pool of mercury.

756
00:52:16,979 --> 00:52:23,980
From it, two massive tungsten-copper alloy
conductors led through the insulum housing,

757
00:52:23,980 --> 00:52:25,309
and outside.

758
00:52:25,309 --> 00:52:31,479
These, so Kendall had hoped, would surge with
the power of broken atoms, but he was beginning

759
00:52:31,479 --> 00:52:34,930
to believe rather bitterly, they would never
do so.

760
00:52:34,930 --> 00:52:39,589
Buck went on to his offices, and the main
calculator room.

761
00:52:39,589 --> 00:52:43,450
There were ten calculator tables here, two
of them in operation now.

762
00:52:43,450 --> 00:52:45,069
"Hello, Devin.

763
00:52:45,069 --> 00:52:46,410
Getting on?"

764
00:52:46,410 --> 00:52:49,650
"No," said Devin bitterly, "I'm getting off.

765
00:52:49,650 --> 00:52:51,400
Look at these results."

766
00:52:51,400 --> 00:52:56,239
He brought over a sheaf of graphs, with explanatory
tables attached.

767
00:52:56,239 --> 00:52:59,160
Rapidly Buck ran through them with him.

768
00:52:59,160 --> 00:53:04,509
Most of them were graphs of functions of light,
considered as a wave in these experiments.

769
00:53:04,509 --> 00:53:07,849
"H-m-m-m—not very encouraging.

770
00:53:07,849 --> 00:53:12,299
Looks like you've got the field—but it just
snaps shut on itself and won't work.

771
00:53:12,299 --> 00:53:17,119
The lack of volume makes it break down, if
you establish it, and makes it impossible

772
00:53:17,119 --> 00:53:21,009
to establish in the first place without the
energy of matter.

773
00:53:21,009 --> 00:53:22,799
Not so hot.

774
00:53:22,799 --> 00:53:24,560
That's certainly cock-eyed somewhere."

775
00:53:24,560 --> 00:53:26,450
"I'm not.

776
00:53:26,450 --> 00:53:27,900
The math may be."

777
00:53:27,900 --> 00:53:31,910
"Well"—Kendall grinned—"it amounts to
the same thing.

778
00:53:31,910 --> 00:53:35,109
The point is, light doesn't.

779
00:53:35,109 --> 00:53:36,940
Let's run over that theory again.

780
00:53:36,940 --> 00:53:40,079
Light is not only magnetic; but electric.

781
00:53:40,079 --> 00:53:46,729
Somehow it transforms electric fields cyclically
into magnetic fields and back again.

782
00:53:46,729 --> 00:53:52,520
Now what we want to do is to transform an
electric into a magnetic field and have it

783
00:53:52,520 --> 00:53:54,180
stay there.

784
00:53:54,180 --> 00:53:55,190
That's the first step.

785
00:53:55,190 --> 00:54:00,559
The second thing, is to have the lines of
magnetic force you develop, lie down like

786
00:54:00,559 --> 00:54:05,560
a sheath around the ship, instead of standing
out like the hairs on an angry cat, the way

787
00:54:05,560 --> 00:54:07,010
they want to.

788
00:54:07,010 --> 00:54:12,049
That means turning them ninety degrees, and
turning an electric into a magnetic field

789
00:54:12,049 --> 00:54:15,910
means turning the space-strain ninety degrees.

790
00:54:15,910 --> 00:54:21,150
Light evidently forms a magnetic field whose
lines of force reach along its direction of

791
00:54:21,150 --> 00:54:24,329
motion, so that's your starting point."

792
00:54:24,329 --> 00:54:29,930
"Yes, and that," growled Devin, "seems to
be the finishing point.

793
00:54:29,930 --> 00:54:34,170
Quite definitely and clearly, the graph looped
down to zero.

794
00:54:34,170 --> 00:54:39,160
In other words, the field closed in on itself,
and destroyed itself."

795
00:54:39,160 --> 00:54:41,640
"Light doesn't vanish."

796
00:54:41,640 --> 00:54:44,140
"I'll make you all the lights you want."

797
00:54:44,140 --> 00:54:47,710
"I simply mean there must be something that
will stop it."

798
00:54:47,710 --> 00:54:48,710
"Certainly.

799
00:54:48,710 --> 00:54:53,519
Transform it back to electric field before
it gets a chance to close in, then repeat

800
00:54:53,519 --> 00:54:55,859
the process—the way light does."

801
00:54:55,859 --> 00:54:59,769
"That wouldn't make such a good magnetic shield.

802
00:54:59,769 --> 00:55:03,530
Every time that field started pulsing out
through the walls of the ship it would generate

803
00:55:03,530 --> 00:55:04,559
heat.

804
00:55:04,559 --> 00:55:08,489
We want a permanent field that will stay on
the job out there.

805
00:55:08,489 --> 00:55:14,049
I wonder if you couldn't make a conductor
device that would open that field out—some

806
00:55:14,049 --> 00:55:17,430
special type of oscillating field that would
keep it open."

807
00:55:17,430 --> 00:55:20,549
"H-m-m-m—that's an angle I might try.

808
00:55:20,549 --> 00:55:21,640
Any suggestions?"

809
00:55:21,640 --> 00:55:27,680
Kendall had suggestions, and rapidly he outlined
a development that appeared from some of the

810
00:55:27,680 --> 00:55:31,390
earlier mathematics on light, and might be
what they wanted.

811
00:55:31,390 --> 00:55:35,380
Kendall, however, had problems of his own
to work on.

812
00:55:35,380 --> 00:55:40,640
The question of atomic energy he was leaving
alone, till the present experiment either

813
00:55:40,640 --> 00:55:45,220
succeeded, or, as he rather suspected, failed
as had its predecessors.

814
00:55:45,220 --> 00:55:50,250
His present problem was to develop more fully
some interesting lines of research he had

815
00:55:50,250 --> 00:55:55,390
run across in investigating mathematically
the trick of turning electric to magnetic

816
00:55:55,390 --> 00:55:57,500
fields and then turning them back again.

817
00:55:57,500 --> 00:56:01,749
It might be that along this line he would
find the answer to the speed greater than

818
00:56:01,749 --> 00:56:02,749
that of light.

819
00:56:02,749 --> 00:56:06,359
At any rate, he was interested.

820
00:56:06,359 --> 00:56:10,680
He worked the rest of that day, and most of
the next on that line—till he ran it into

821
00:56:10,680 --> 00:56:19,259
the ground with a pair of equations that ended
with the expression: dx.dv=h/(4πm).

822
00:56:19,259 --> 00:56:24,989
Then Kendall looked at them for a long moment,
then he sighed gently and threw them into

823
00:56:24,989 --> 00:56:26,739
a file cabinet.

824
00:56:26,739 --> 00:56:28,700
Heisenberg's Uncertainty.

825
00:56:28,700 --> 00:56:34,109
He'd reduced the thing to a form that simply
told him it was beyond the limits of certainty

826
00:56:34,109 --> 00:56:40,969
and he ran it into the normal, natural uncertainty
inevitable in Nature.

827
00:56:40,969 --> 00:56:43,400
Anyway he had real work to do now.

828
00:56:43,400 --> 00:56:46,109
The machine was about ready for his attention.

829
00:56:46,109 --> 00:56:50,440
The mechanicians had finished putting it in
shape for demonstration and trial.

830
00:56:50,440 --> 00:56:54,089
He himself would have to test it over the
rest of the afternoon and arrange for power

831
00:56:54,089 --> 00:56:55,410
and so forth.

832
00:56:55,410 --> 00:57:00,690
By evening, when Commander McLaurin called
around with some of the other investors in

833
00:57:00,690 --> 00:57:04,970
Kendall's "bank" on Luna, the thing was already
started, warming up.

834
00:57:04,970 --> 00:57:09,450
The fields were being fed and the various
scientists of the group were watching with

835
00:57:09,450 --> 00:57:11,130
interest.

836
00:57:11,130 --> 00:57:15,329
Power was flowing in already at a rate of
nearly one hundred thousand horsepower per

837
00:57:15,329 --> 00:57:20,369
minute, thanks to a special line given them
by New York Power (a Kendall property).

838
00:57:20,369 --> 00:57:25,249
At ten o'clock they were beginning to expect
the reaction to start.

839
00:57:25,249 --> 00:57:30,430
By this time the fields weren't gaining in
intensity very rapidly, a maximum intensity

840
00:57:30,430 --> 00:57:34,229
had been reached that should, they felt, break
the atoms soon.

841
00:57:34,229 --> 00:57:39,880
At eleven-thirty, through the little view
window, Buck Kendall saw something that made

842
00:57:39,880 --> 00:57:42,470
him cry out in amazement.

843
00:57:42,470 --> 00:57:48,170
The mercury metal in the receiver, behind
its layers of screening was beginning to glow,

844
00:57:48,170 --> 00:57:53,619
with a dull reddish light, and little solidifications
were appearing in it!

845
00:57:53,619 --> 00:57:59,219
Eagerly the men looked, as the solidifications
spread slowly, like crystals growing in an

846
00:57:59,219 --> 00:58:00,980
evaporating solution.

847
00:58:00,980 --> 00:58:06,410
Twelve o'clock came and went, and one o'clock
and two o'clock.

848
00:58:06,410 --> 00:58:10,150
Still the slow crystallization went on.

849
00:58:10,150 --> 00:58:14,009
Buck Kendall was casting furtive glances at
the kilowatt-hour meter.

850
00:58:14,009 --> 00:58:21,089
It stood at a figure that represented twenty-seven
thousand dollars' worth of power.

851
00:58:21,089 --> 00:58:25,690
Long since the power rate had been increased
to the maximum available, as the power plant's

852
00:58:25,690 --> 00:58:29,069
normal load reduced as the morning hours came.

853
00:58:29,069 --> 00:58:34,920
Surely, this time something would start, but
Buck had two worries.

854
00:58:34,920 --> 00:58:39,450
If all the enormous amount of energy they
had poured in there decided to release itself

855
00:58:39,450 --> 00:58:40,450
at once—

856
00:58:40,450 --> 00:58:46,319
And at any rate, Buck saw they'd never dare
to let a generator stop, once it was started!

857
00:58:46,319 --> 00:58:50,509
The men were a tense group around the machine
at three-fifteen a.m.

858
00:58:50,509 --> 00:58:56,829
There remained only a tiny, dancing globule
of silvery mercury skittering around on the

859
00:58:56,829 --> 00:59:01,380
sharp, needle-like crystals of the dull red
metal that had resulted.

860
00:59:01,380 --> 00:59:05,569
Slowly that skittering drop was shrinking—

861
00:59:05,569 --> 00:59:09,950
Three twenty-two and a half a.m. saw the last
fraction of it vanish.

862
00:59:09,950 --> 00:59:16,319
Tensely the men stared into the machine—backing
off slowly—watching the meters on the board.

863
00:59:16,319 --> 00:59:21,430
At nearly eighty thousand volts the power
had been fed into it.

864
00:59:21,430 --> 00:59:26,950
The power continued to flow, and a growing
halo of intense violet light appeared suddenly

865
00:59:26,950 --> 00:59:31,650
on those red, needle-like crystals, a swiftly
expanding halo—

866
00:59:31,650 --> 00:59:39,790
Without a sound, without the slightest disturbance,
the halo vanished, and softly, gently, the

867
00:59:39,790 --> 00:59:45,869
needle-like crystals relapsed, melted away,
and a dull pool of metallic mercury rested

868
00:59:45,869 --> 00:59:47,420
in the receiver.

869
00:59:47,420 --> 00:59:51,970
At eighty thousand volts, power was flowing
in—

870
00:59:51,970 --> 01:00:02,650
And it didn't even sparkle.

871
01:00:02,650 --> 01:00:17,000
V
The apparatus of the magnetic shield had been

872
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:20,599
completed two days later, and set up in Buck's
own laboratory.

873
01:00:20,599 --> 01:00:26,130
On the bench was the powerful, but small,
little projector of the straight magnetic

874
01:00:26,130 --> 01:00:31,719
field, simply a specially designed accumulator,
a super-condenser, and the peculiar apparatus

875
01:00:31,719 --> 01:00:36,710
Devin had designed to distort the electric
field through ninety degrees to a magnetic

876
01:00:36,710 --> 01:00:37,720
field.

877
01:00:37,720 --> 01:00:43,470
Behind this was a curious, paraboloid projector
made up of hundreds of tiny, carefully orientated

878
01:00:43,470 --> 01:00:44,470
coils.

879
01:00:44,470 --> 01:00:47,440
This was Buck's own contribution.

880
01:00:47,440 --> 01:00:49,770
They were ready for the tests.

881
01:00:49,770 --> 01:00:55,890
"I would invite McLaurin in to see this,"
said Kendall looking at them, and then across

882
01:00:55,890 --> 01:01:01,390
the room bitterly toward the alleged atomic
power apparatus on the opposite bench.

883
01:01:01,390 --> 01:01:03,479
"I think it will work.

884
01:01:03,479 --> 01:01:09,309
But after that—" He stared, glaring, at
the heavy tungsten dome with its heavy tungsten

885
01:01:09,309 --> 01:01:14,760
contacts, across which the flame of released
atomic energy was supposed to have leapt.

886
01:01:14,760 --> 01:01:19,880
"That was probably the flattest flop any experiment
ever flopped."

887
01:01:19,880 --> 01:01:22,930
"Well—it didn't blow up.

888
01:01:22,930 --> 01:01:25,489
That's one comfort," suggested Devin.

889
01:01:25,489 --> 01:01:27,329
"I wish it had.

890
01:01:27,329 --> 01:01:31,029
Then at least it would have shown some response.

891
01:01:31,029 --> 01:01:34,719
The only response shown, actually, was shown
on the power meter.

892
01:01:34,719 --> 01:01:38,640
It damn near wore out the bearings turning
so fast."

893
01:01:38,640 --> 01:01:41,450
"Personally, I prefer the lack of action."

894
01:01:41,450 --> 01:01:42,450
Devin laughed.

895
01:01:42,450 --> 01:01:45,119
"Have you got that circuit hooked up?"

896
01:01:45,119 --> 01:01:48,650
"Right," sighed Kendall, turning back to the
work in hand.

897
01:01:48,650 --> 01:01:50,730
"Is Douglass in on this?"

898
01:01:50,730 --> 01:01:52,759
"Yes—in the next room.

899
01:01:52,759 --> 01:01:54,599
He'll let us know when he's ready.

900
01:01:54,599 --> 01:01:55,859
He's setting up those instruments."

901
01:01:55,859 --> 01:02:02,299
Douglass, a young junior physicist, late of
the IP Physics Department, stuck his head

902
01:02:02,299 --> 01:02:04,930
in the door and announced his instruments
were all set up.

903
01:02:04,930 --> 01:02:06,680
"Keep an eye on them.

904
01:02:06,680 --> 01:02:08,859
They'll move somehow, at any rate.

905
01:02:08,859 --> 01:02:13,380
This thing couldn't go as flat as that atom-buster
of mine."

906
01:02:13,380 --> 01:02:18,989
Carefully Kendall made a few last-minute adjustments
on the limiting relays, and took up his position

907
01:02:18,989 --> 01:02:20,410
at the power board.

908
01:02:20,410 --> 01:02:25,579
Devin took his place near the apparatus, with
another series of instruments, similar to

909
01:02:25,579 --> 01:02:29,749
those Douglass was now watching in the next
room, some thirty feet away, through the two-inch

910
01:02:29,749 --> 01:02:31,020
metal wall.

911
01:02:31,020 --> 01:02:33,540
"Ready," called Kendall.

912
01:02:33,540 --> 01:02:36,900
The switch shot home.

913
01:02:36,900 --> 01:02:40,979
Instantly Kendall, Devin, and all the men
in the building jumped some six feet from

914
01:02:40,979 --> 01:02:42,660
their former positions.

915
01:02:42,660 --> 01:02:49,079
A monstrous roar of sound crashed out in that
laboratory that thundered from one wall to

916
01:02:49,079 --> 01:02:52,420
the other, and bellowed in a Titan's fury.

917
01:02:52,420 --> 01:02:57,680
It thundered and growled, it bellowed and
howled, the walls shook with the march and

918
01:02:57,680 --> 01:03:00,210
counter-march of crashing waves of sound.

919
01:03:00,210 --> 01:03:06,970
And a ten-foot wavering flame of blue-white,
bellying electric fire shuddered up to the

920
01:03:06,970 --> 01:03:11,609
ceiling from the contact points of the alleged
atomic generator.

921
01:03:11,609 --> 01:03:17,239
The heat, pouring out from the flashing, roaring
arc sent prickles of aching burns over Kendall's

922
01:03:17,239 --> 01:03:18,239
skin.

923
01:03:18,239 --> 01:03:24,790
For ten seconds he stood in utter, paralyzed
surprise as his flop of flops bellowed its

924
01:03:24,790 --> 01:03:26,559
anger at his disdain.

925
01:03:26,559 --> 01:03:31,269
Then he leapt to the power board and shut
off the roaring thing, by cutting the switch

926
01:03:31,269 --> 01:03:33,019
that had started it.

927
01:03:33,019 --> 01:03:35,809
"Spirits of Space!

928
01:03:35,809 --> 01:03:37,930
Did that come to life!"

929
01:03:37,930 --> 01:03:39,589
"Atomic Energy!"

930
01:03:39,589 --> 01:03:41,250
Devin cried.

931
01:03:41,250 --> 01:03:43,739
"Atomic energy, hell.

932
01:03:43,739 --> 01:03:48,319
That's my thirty thousand dollars' worth of
power breaking loose again," chortled Kendall.

933
01:03:48,319 --> 01:03:55,089
"We missed the atomic energy, but, sweet boy,
what an accumulator we stubbed our toes on!

934
01:03:55,089 --> 01:03:59,400
I wondered where in blazes all that power
went to.

935
01:03:59,400 --> 01:04:00,609
That's the answer.

936
01:04:00,609 --> 01:04:03,519
I'll bet I can tell you right now what happened.

937
01:04:03,519 --> 01:04:10,390
We built that mercury up to a new level, and
that transitional stage was the red, crystalline

938
01:04:10,390 --> 01:04:11,460
metal.

939
01:04:11,460 --> 01:04:16,549
When it reached the higher stage, it was temporarily
stable—but that projector over there that

940
01:04:16,549 --> 01:04:21,470
we designed for the purpose of holding open
electric and magnetic fields just opened the

941
01:04:21,470 --> 01:04:25,200
door and let all that power right out again."

942
01:04:25,200 --> 01:04:28,489
"But why isn't it atomic energy?

943
01:04:28,489 --> 01:04:32,059
How do you know that no more than your power
that you put in is coming out?"

944
01:04:32,059 --> 01:04:33,180
demanded Devin.

945
01:04:33,180 --> 01:04:36,569
"The arc, man, the arc.

946
01:04:36,569 --> 01:04:38,910
That was a high-current, and low-voltage arc.

947
01:04:38,910 --> 01:04:44,569
Couldn't you tell by the sound that no great
voltage—as atomic voltages go—was smashing

948
01:04:44,569 --> 01:04:45,829
across there?

949
01:04:45,829 --> 01:04:51,400
If we were getting atomic voltage—and power—there'd
have been a different tone to it, high and

950
01:04:51,400 --> 01:04:52,500
shriller.

951
01:04:52,500 --> 01:04:54,630
"Now, did you take any readings?"

952
01:04:54,630 --> 01:04:56,700
"What do you think, man?

953
01:04:56,700 --> 01:04:57,819
I'm human.

954
01:04:57,819 --> 01:05:02,049
Do you think I got any readings with that
thing bellowing and shrieking in my ears,

955
01:05:02,049 --> 01:05:04,819
and burning my skin with ultra-violet?

956
01:05:04,819 --> 01:05:06,150
It itches now."

957
01:05:06,150 --> 01:05:07,869
Kendall laughed.

958
01:05:07,869 --> 01:05:10,619
"You know what to do for an itch.

959
01:05:10,619 --> 01:05:13,410
Now, I'm going to make a bet.

960
01:05:13,410 --> 01:05:19,309
We had those points separated for a half-million
volts discharge, but there was a dust-cover

961
01:05:19,309 --> 01:05:21,390
thrown over them just now.

962
01:05:21,390 --> 01:05:23,900
That, you notice, is missing.

963
01:05:23,900 --> 01:05:27,299
I'll bet that served as a starter lead for
the main arc.

964
01:05:27,299 --> 01:05:32,499
Now I'm going to start that projector thing
again, and move the points there through about

965
01:05:32,499 --> 01:05:38,210
six inches, and that thing probably won't
start itself."

966
01:05:38,210 --> 01:05:42,130
Most of the laboratory staff had collected
at the doorway, looking in at the white-hot

967
01:05:42,130 --> 01:05:47,460
tungsten discharge points, and the now silent
"atomic engine."

968
01:05:47,460 --> 01:05:51,630
Kendall turned to them and said: "The flop
picked itself up.

969
01:05:51,630 --> 01:05:55,140
You go on back, we seem to be all in one piece
yet.

970
01:05:55,140 --> 01:05:59,170
Douglass, you didn't get any readings, did
you?"

971
01:05:59,170 --> 01:06:01,749
Sheepishly, Douglass grinned at him.

972
01:06:01,749 --> 01:06:04,819
"Eh—er—no—but I tore my pants.

973
01:06:04,819 --> 01:06:07,180
The magnetic field grabbed me and I jumped.

974
01:06:07,180 --> 01:06:12,589
They had some steel buttons, and a lot of
steel keys—they're kinda' hard to keep on

975
01:06:12,589 --> 01:06:13,989
now."

976
01:06:13,989 --> 01:06:19,220
The laboratory staff broke into a roar of
laughter, as Douglass, holding up his trousers

977
01:06:19,220 --> 01:06:21,380
with both hands was beheld.

978
01:06:21,380 --> 01:06:25,029
"I guess the field worked," he said.

979
01:06:25,029 --> 01:06:29,109
"I guess maybe it did," adjudged Kendall solemnly.

980
01:06:29,109 --> 01:06:32,589
"We have some rope here if you need it—"

981
01:06:32,589 --> 01:06:34,839
Douglass returned to his post.

982
01:06:34,839 --> 01:06:41,349
Swiftly, Kendall altered the atomic distortion
storage apparatus, and returned to the power-board.

983
01:06:41,349 --> 01:06:42,849
"Ready?"

984
01:06:42,849 --> 01:06:44,349
"Check."

985
01:06:44,349 --> 01:06:46,470
Kendall shoved home the switch.

986
01:06:46,470 --> 01:06:49,599
The storage device was silent.

987
01:06:49,599 --> 01:06:54,989
Only a slight feeling of strain made itself
felt, and the sudden noisy hum of a small

988
01:06:54,989 --> 01:06:56,759
transformer nearby.

989
01:06:56,759 --> 01:06:58,999
"She works, Buck!"

990
01:06:58,999 --> 01:06:59,999
Devin called.

991
01:06:59,999 --> 01:07:01,489
"The readings check almost exactly."

992
01:07:01,489 --> 01:07:04,609
"All good then.

993
01:07:04,609 --> 01:07:07,459
Now I want to get to that atomic thing.

994
01:07:07,459 --> 01:07:11,190
We can let that slide for a little bit—I'll
answer it."

995
01:07:11,190 --> 01:07:13,770
The telephone had rung noisily.

996
01:07:13,770 --> 01:07:16,240
"Kendall Labs—Kendall speaking."

997
01:07:16,240 --> 01:07:21,729
"This is Superintendent Foster, of the New
York Power, Mr. Kendall.

998
01:07:21,729 --> 01:07:26,510
We have some trouble just now that we think
your operations may be responsible for.

999
01:07:26,510 --> 01:07:31,579
The sub-station at North Beaumont blew all
the fuses, and threw the breakers at the main

1000
01:07:31,579 --> 01:07:32,579
station.

1001
01:07:32,579 --> 01:07:35,529
The men out there said the transformers began
howling—"

1002
01:07:35,529 --> 01:07:39,010
"Right you are—I'm afraid I did do that.

1003
01:07:39,010 --> 01:07:42,049
I had no idea that it would reach so far.

1004
01:07:42,049 --> 01:07:44,530
How far is that from my place here?"

1005
01:07:44,530 --> 01:07:48,390
"It's about a thousand yards, according to
the survey maps."

1006
01:07:48,390 --> 01:07:51,609
"Thanks—and I'll be careful about it.

1007
01:07:51,609 --> 01:07:53,790
Any damage, I am responsible for?

1008
01:07:53,790 --> 01:07:54,790
All okay?"

1009
01:07:54,790 --> 01:07:56,849
"Yes, sir, Mr. Kendall."

1010
01:07:56,849 --> 01:07:59,319
Kendall hung up.

1011
01:07:59,319 --> 01:08:03,029
"We stirred up a lot more dust than we expected,
Devin.

1012
01:08:03,029 --> 01:08:05,829
Now let's start seeing if we can keep track
of it.

1013
01:08:05,829 --> 01:08:08,180
Douglass, how did your readings show?"

1014
01:08:08,180 --> 01:08:11,059
"I took them at the ten stations, and here
they are.

1015
01:08:11,059 --> 01:08:12,539
The stations are two feet apart."

1016
01:08:12,539 --> 01:08:17,140
"H-m-m—.5—.55—.6—.7—20—198—5950—6010—6012—5920.

1017
01:08:17,140 --> 01:08:33,609
Very, very nice—only the darned thing's
got an arm as long as the law.

1018
01:08:33,609 --> 01:08:36,390
Your readings were about .2, Devin?"

1019
01:08:36,390 --> 01:08:37,920
"That's right."

1020
01:08:37,920 --> 01:08:40,940
"Then these little readings are just leakage.

1021
01:08:40,940 --> 01:08:43,060
What's our normal intensity here?"

1022
01:08:43,060 --> 01:08:45,180
"About .19.

1023
01:08:45,180 --> 01:08:48,920
Just a very small fraction less than the readings."

1024
01:08:48,920 --> 01:08:55,420
"Perfect—we have what amounts to a hollow
shell of magnetic force—we can move inside,

1025
01:08:55,420 --> 01:08:57,500
and you can move outside—far enough.

1026
01:08:57,500 --> 01:09:01,549
But you can't get a conductor or a magnetic
field through it."

1027
01:09:01,549 --> 01:09:05,119
He put the readings on the bench, and looked
at the apparatus across the room.

1028
01:09:05,119 --> 01:09:08,869
"Now I want to start right on that other.

1029
01:09:08,869 --> 01:09:14,009
Douglass, you move that magnetostat apparatus
out of the way, and leave just the 'can-opener'

1030
01:09:14,009 --> 01:09:16,210
of ours—the projector.

1031
01:09:16,210 --> 01:09:18,940
I'm pretty sure that's what does the deed.

1032
01:09:18,940 --> 01:09:23,829
Devin, see if you can hunt up some electrostatic
voltmeters with a range in the neighborhood

1033
01:09:23,829 --> 01:09:27,510
of—I think it'll be about eighty thousand."

1034
01:09:27,510 --> 01:09:33,089
Rapidly, Douglass was dismounting the apparatus,
as Devin started for the stock room.

1035
01:09:33,089 --> 01:09:37,880
Kendall started making some new connections,
reconnecting the apparatus they had intended

1036
01:09:37,880 --> 01:09:42,469
using on the "atomic engine," largely high-capacity
resistances.

1037
01:09:42,469 --> 01:09:49,620
He seemed to perform this work mechanically,
his mind definitely on something else.

1038
01:09:49,620 --> 01:09:54,170
Suddenly he stopped, and looked carefully
into the receiver of the machine.

1039
01:09:54,170 --> 01:09:59,970
The metal in it was silvery, liquid, and here
and there a floating crystal of the dull red

1040
01:09:59,970 --> 01:10:02,050
metal.

1041
01:10:02,050 --> 01:10:04,739
Slowly a smile spread across his face.

1042
01:10:04,739 --> 01:10:06,699
He turned to Douglass.

1043
01:10:06,699 --> 01:10:09,010
"Douglass—ah, you're through.

1044
01:10:09,010 --> 01:10:13,340
Get on the trail of MacBride, and get him
and his crew to work making half a dozen smaller

1045
01:10:13,340 --> 01:10:15,280
things like this.

1046
01:10:15,280 --> 01:10:17,469
Tell 'em they can leave off the tungsten shield.

1047
01:10:17,469 --> 01:10:21,040
I want different metals in the receiver of
each.

1048
01:10:21,040 --> 01:10:26,390
Use—hmmm—sodium—copper—magnesium—aluminium,
iron and chromium.

1049
01:10:26,390 --> 01:10:27,449
Got it?"

1050
01:10:27,449 --> 01:10:29,430
"Yes, sir."

1051
01:10:29,430 --> 01:10:33,420
He left, just as Devin returned with a large
electrostatic voltmeter.

1052
01:10:33,420 --> 01:10:42,719
"I'd like," said he, "to know how you know
the voltage will range around eighty thousand."

1053
01:10:42,719 --> 01:10:45,070
"K-ring excitation potential for mercury.

1054
01:10:45,070 --> 01:10:50,450
I'm willing to bet that thing simply shoved
the whole electron system of the mercury out

1055
01:10:50,450 --> 01:10:55,030
a notch—that it simply hasn't any K-ring
of electrons now.

1056
01:10:55,030 --> 01:10:57,010
I'm trying some other metals.

1057
01:10:57,010 --> 01:11:01,100
Douglass is going to have MacBride make up
half a dozen more machines.

1058
01:11:01,100 --> 01:11:04,080
Machines—they need a name.

1059
01:11:04,080 --> 01:11:07,070
This—ah—this is an 'atostor.'

1060
01:11:07,070 --> 01:11:11,969
MacBride's going to make up half a dozen of
'em, and try half a dozen metals.

1061
01:11:11,969 --> 01:11:16,110
I'm almost certain that's not mercury in there
now, at all.

1062
01:11:16,110 --> 01:11:19,389
It's probably element 99 or something like
it."

1063
01:11:19,389 --> 01:11:21,810
"It looks like mercury—"

1064
01:11:21,810 --> 01:11:22,810
"Certainly.

1065
01:11:22,810 --> 01:11:25,650
So would 99.

1066
01:11:25,650 --> 01:11:30,880
Following the periodic table, 99 would probably
have an even lower melting point than mercury,

1067
01:11:30,880 --> 01:11:35,030
be silvery, dense and heavy—and perhaps
slightly radioactive.

1068
01:11:35,030 --> 01:11:41,920
The series under the B family of Group II
is Magnesium, Zinc, Cadmium, Mercury—and

1069
01:11:41,920 --> 01:11:42,920
99.

1070
01:11:42,920 --> 01:11:47,260
The melting point is going down all the way,
and they're all silvery metals.

1071
01:11:47,260 --> 01:11:54,320
I'm going to try copper, and I fully expect
it to turn silvery—in fact, to become silver."

1072
01:11:54,320 --> 01:11:55,840
"Then let's see."

1073
01:11:55,840 --> 01:12:01,199
Swiftly they hooked up the apparatus, realigned
the projector, and again Kendall took his

1074
01:12:01,199 --> 01:12:03,280
place at the power-board.

1075
01:12:03,280 --> 01:12:09,349
As he closed the switch, on no-load, the electrostatic
voltmeter flopped over instantly, and steadied

1076
01:12:09,349 --> 01:12:12,219
at just over 80,000 volts.

1077
01:12:12,219 --> 01:12:16,060
"I hate to say 'I told you so,'" said Kendall.

1078
01:12:16,060 --> 01:12:18,170
"But let's hook in a load.

1079
01:12:18,170 --> 01:12:21,590
Try it on about 100 amps first."

1080
01:12:21,590 --> 01:12:24,670
Devin began cutting in load.

1081
01:12:24,670 --> 01:12:28,900
The resistors began heating up swiftly as
more and more current flowed through them.

1082
01:12:28,900 --> 01:12:35,670
By not so much as by a vibration of the voltmeter
needle, did the apparatus betray any strain

1083
01:12:35,670 --> 01:12:38,780
as the load mounted swiftly.

1084
01:12:38,780 --> 01:12:42,060
100—200—500—1000 amperes.

1085
01:12:42,060 --> 01:12:45,440
Still, that needle held steady.

1086
01:12:45,440 --> 01:12:50,780
Finally, with a drain of ten thousand amperes,
all the equipment available could handle,

1087
01:12:50,780 --> 01:12:56,170
the needle was steady as a rock, though the
tremendous load of 800,000,000 watts was cut

1088
01:12:56,170 --> 01:12:57,670
in and out.

1089
01:12:57,670 --> 01:13:05,030
That, to atoms, atoms by the nonillions, was
no appreciable load at all.

1090
01:13:05,030 --> 01:13:09,060
There was no internal resistance whatever.

1091
01:13:09,060 --> 01:13:12,869
The perfect accumulator had certainly been
discovered.

1092
01:13:12,869 --> 01:13:20,540
"I'll have to call McLaurin—" Kendall hurried
away with a broad, broad smile.

1093
01:13:20,540 --> 01:13:31,360
VI
"Hello, Tom?"

1094
01:13:31,360 --> 01:13:42,349
The 
telephone rattled in a peeved sort of way.

1095
01:13:42,349 --> 01:13:44,130
"Yes, it is.

1096
01:13:44,130 --> 01:13:45,329
What now?

1097
01:13:45,329 --> 01:13:48,650
And when am I going to see you in a social
sort of way again?"

1098
01:13:48,650 --> 01:13:52,250
"Not for a long, long time; I'm busy.

1099
01:13:52,250 --> 01:13:54,230
I'm busy right now as a matter of fact.

1100
01:13:54,230 --> 01:13:58,909
I'm calling up the vice-president of Faragaut
Interplanetary Lines, and I want to place

1101
01:13:58,909 --> 01:13:59,909
an order."

1102
01:13:59,909 --> 01:14:01,949
"Why bother me?

1103
01:14:01,949 --> 01:14:07,060
We have clerks, you know, for that sort of
thing," suggested Faragaut in a pained voice.

1104
01:14:07,060 --> 01:14:10,520
"Tom, do you know how much I'm worth now?"

1105
01:14:10,520 --> 01:14:13,650
"Not much," replied Faragaut promptly.

1106
01:14:13,650 --> 01:14:14,940
"What of it?

1107
01:14:14,940 --> 01:14:18,440
I hear, as a matter of fact that you're worth
even less in a business way.

1108
01:14:18,440 --> 01:14:23,090
They're talking quite a lot down this way
about an alleged bank you're setting up on

1109
01:14:23,090 --> 01:14:24,090
Luna.

1110
01:14:24,090 --> 01:14:29,690
I hear it's got more protective devices, and
armor than any IP station in the System, that

1111
01:14:29,690 --> 01:14:35,030
you even had it designed by an IP designer,
and have a gang of Colonels and Generals in

1112
01:14:35,030 --> 01:14:36,030
charge.

1113
01:14:36,030 --> 01:14:39,989
I also hear that you've succeeded in getting
rid of money at about one million dollars

1114
01:14:39,989 --> 01:14:43,099
a day—just slightly shy of that."

1115
01:14:43,099 --> 01:14:45,679
"You overestimate me, my friend.

1116
01:14:45,679 --> 01:14:48,250
Much of that is merely contracted for.

1117
01:14:48,250 --> 01:14:51,929
Actually it'll take me nearly nine months
to get rid of it.

1118
01:14:51,929 --> 01:14:54,150
And by that time I'll have more.

1119
01:14:54,150 --> 01:14:58,520
Anyway, I think I have something like ten
million left.

1120
01:14:58,520 --> 01:15:03,340
And remember that way back in the twentieth
century some old fellow beat my record.

1121
01:15:03,340 --> 01:15:09,000
Armour, I think it was, lost a million dollars
a day for a couple of months running.

1122
01:15:09,000 --> 01:15:14,989
"Anyway, what I called you up for was to say
I'd like to order five hundred thousand tons

1123
01:15:14,989 --> 01:15:18,110
of mercury, for delivery as soon as possible."

1124
01:15:18,110 --> 01:15:19,110
"What!

1125
01:15:19,110 --> 01:15:22,670
Oh, say, I thought you were going in for business."

1126
01:15:22,670 --> 01:15:25,650
Faragaut gave a slight laugh of relief.

1127
01:15:25,650 --> 01:15:27,750
"Tom, I am.

1128
01:15:27,750 --> 01:15:30,170
I mean exactly what I say.

1129
01:15:30,170 --> 01:15:37,350
I want five—hundred—thousand—tons of
metallic mercury, and just as soon as you

1130
01:15:37,350 --> 01:15:38,820
can get it."

1131
01:15:38,820 --> 01:15:42,179
"Man, there isn't that much in the system."

1132
01:15:42,179 --> 01:15:43,630
"I know it.

1133
01:15:43,630 --> 01:15:48,489
Get all there is on the market for me, and
contract to take all the 'Jupiter Heavy-Metals'

1134
01:15:48,489 --> 01:15:50,219
can turn out.

1135
01:15:50,219 --> 01:15:54,590
You send those orders through, and clean out
the market completely.

1136
01:15:54,590 --> 01:15:58,151
Somebody's about to pay for the work I've
been doing, and boy, they're going to pay

1137
01:15:58,151 --> 01:16:00,239
through the nose.

1138
01:16:00,239 --> 01:16:04,300
After you've got that order launched, and
don't make a christening party of the launching

1139
01:16:04,300 --> 01:16:09,909
either, why just drop out here, and I'll show
you why the value of mercury is going so high

1140
01:16:09,909 --> 01:16:14,030
you won't be able to follow it in a space
ship."

1141
01:16:14,030 --> 01:16:20,321
"The cost of that," said Faragaut, seriously
now, "will be about—fifty-three million

1142
01:16:20,321 --> 01:16:21,610
at the market price.

1143
01:16:21,610 --> 01:16:25,829
You'd have to put up twenty-six cash, and
I don't believe you've got it."

1144
01:16:25,829 --> 01:16:27,070
Buck laughed.

1145
01:16:27,070 --> 01:16:30,920
"Tom, loan me a dozen million, will you?

1146
01:16:30,920 --> 01:16:34,040
You send that order through, and then come
see what I've got.

1147
01:16:34,040 --> 01:16:36,570
I've got a break, too!

1148
01:16:36,570 --> 01:16:41,159
Mercury's the best metal for this use—and
it'll stop gamma rays too!"

1149
01:16:41,159 --> 01:16:46,360
"So it will—but for the love of the system,
what of it?"

1150
01:16:46,360 --> 01:16:48,070
"Come and see—tonight.

1151
01:16:48,070 --> 01:16:50,400
Will you send that order through?"

1152
01:16:50,400 --> 01:16:52,250
"I will, Buck.

1153
01:16:52,250 --> 01:16:53,409
I hope you're right.

1154
01:16:53,409 --> 01:16:57,980
Cash is tight now, and I'll probably have
to put up nearer twenty million, when all

1155
01:16:57,980 --> 01:16:59,530
that buying goes through.

1156
01:16:59,530 --> 01:17:03,480
How long will it be tied up in that deal,
do you think?"

1157
01:17:03,480 --> 01:17:05,060
"Not over three weeks.

1158
01:17:05,060 --> 01:17:10,750
And I'll guarantee you three hundred percent—if
you'll stay in with me after you start.

1159
01:17:10,750 --> 01:17:14,969
Otherwise—I don't think making this money
would be fair just now."

1160
01:17:14,969 --> 01:17:18,449
"I'll be out to see you in about two hours,
Buck.

1161
01:17:18,449 --> 01:17:19,590
Where are you?

1162
01:17:19,590 --> 01:17:21,690
At the estate?" asked Faragaut seriously.

1163
01:17:21,690 --> 01:17:24,310
"In my lab out there.

1164
01:17:24,310 --> 01:17:26,150
Thanks, Tom."

1165
01:17:26,150 --> 01:17:29,800
McLaurin was there when Tom Faragaut arrived.

1166
01:17:29,800 --> 01:17:33,000
And General Logan, and Colonel Gerardhi.

1167
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:37,780
There was a restrained air of gratefulness
about all of them that Tom Faragaut couldn't

1168
01:17:37,780 --> 01:17:39,820
quite understand.

1169
01:17:39,820 --> 01:17:44,449
He had been looking up Buck Kendall's famous
bank, and more and more he had begun to wonder

1170
01:17:44,449 --> 01:17:46,780
just what was up.

1171
01:17:46,780 --> 01:17:51,219
The list of stockholders had read like a list
of IP heroes and executives.

1172
01:17:51,219 --> 01:17:56,889
The staff had been a list of IP men with a
slender sprinkling of accountants.

1173
01:17:56,889 --> 01:18:03,270
And the sixty-million dollar structure was
to be a bank without advertising of any sort!

1174
01:18:03,270 --> 01:18:06,810
Usually such a venture is planned and published
months in advance.

1175
01:18:06,810 --> 01:18:12,250
This had sprung up suddenly, with a strange
quietness.

1176
01:18:12,250 --> 01:18:15,500
Almost silently, Buck Kendall led the way
to the laboratory.

1177
01:18:15,500 --> 01:18:22,000
A small metal tank was supported in a peculiar
piece of apparatus, and from it led a small

1178
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:27,409
platinum pipe to a domed apparatus made largely
of insulum.

1179
01:18:27,409 --> 01:18:33,560
A little pool of mercury, with small red crystals
floating in it rested in a shallow hollow

1180
01:18:33,560 --> 01:18:35,580
surrounded by heavy conductors.

1181
01:18:35,580 --> 01:18:37,199
"That's it, Tom.

1182
01:18:37,199 --> 01:18:42,460
I wanted to show you first what we have, and
why I wanted all that mercury.

1183
01:18:42,460 --> 01:18:47,989
Within three weeks, every man, woman and child
in the system will be clamoring for mercury

1184
01:18:47,989 --> 01:18:49,599
metal.

1185
01:18:49,599 --> 01:18:52,820
That's the perfect accumulator."

1186
01:18:52,820 --> 01:18:57,320
Quickly he demonstrated the machine, charging
it, and then discharging it.

1187
01:18:57,320 --> 01:19:05,560
It was better than 99.95% efficient on the
charge, and was 100% efficient on the discharge.

1188
01:19:05,560 --> 01:19:08,579
"Physically, any metal will do.

1189
01:19:08,579 --> 01:19:11,260
Technically, mercury is best for a number
of reasons.

1190
01:19:11,260 --> 01:19:12,780
It's a liquid.

1191
01:19:12,780 --> 01:19:18,219
I can, and do it in this, charge a certain
quantity, and then move it up to the storage

1192
01:19:18,219 --> 01:19:19,219
tank.

1193
01:19:19,219 --> 01:19:21,159
Charge another pool, and move it up.

1194
01:19:21,159 --> 01:19:27,650
In discharge, I can let a stream flow in continuously
if I required a steady, terrific drain of

1195
01:19:27,650 --> 01:19:29,540
power without interruption.

1196
01:19:29,540 --> 01:19:36,050
If I wanted it for more normal service, I'd
discharge a pool, drain it, refill the receiver,

1197
01:19:36,050 --> 01:19:38,280
and discharge a second pool.

1198
01:19:38,280 --> 01:19:41,040
Thus, mercury is the metal to use.

1199
01:19:41,040 --> 01:19:44,270
"Do you see why I wanted all that metal?"

1200
01:19:44,270 --> 01:19:49,030
"I do, Buck—Lord, I do," gasped Faragaut.

1201
01:19:49,030 --> 01:19:51,810
"That is the perfect power supply."

1202
01:19:51,810 --> 01:19:54,380
"No, confound it, it isn't.

1203
01:19:54,380 --> 01:19:56,550
It's a secondary source.

1204
01:19:56,550 --> 01:19:57,949
It isn't primary.

1205
01:19:57,949 --> 01:20:03,829
We're just as limited in the supply of power
as ever—only we have increased our distribution

1206
01:20:03,829 --> 01:20:04,829
of power.

1207
01:20:04,829 --> 01:20:10,829
Lord knows, we're going to need a power supply
badly enough before long—" Buck relapsed

1208
01:20:10,829 --> 01:20:12,560
into moody silence.

1209
01:20:12,560 --> 01:20:17,250
"What," asked Faragaut, looking around him,
"does that mean?"

1210
01:20:17,250 --> 01:20:22,969
It was McLaurin who told him of the stranger
ship, and Kendall's interpretation of its

1211
01:20:22,969 --> 01:20:24,480
meaning.

1212
01:20:24,480 --> 01:20:30,270
Slowly Faragaut grasped the meaning behind
Buck's strange actions of the past months.

1213
01:20:30,270 --> 01:20:35,270
"The Lunar Bank," he said slowly, half to
himself.

1214
01:20:35,270 --> 01:20:39,929
"Staffed by trained IP men, experts in expert
destruction.

1215
01:20:39,929 --> 01:20:43,580
Buck, you said something about the profits
of this venture.

1216
01:20:43,580 --> 01:20:44,790
What did you mean?"

1217
01:20:44,790 --> 01:20:46,719
Buck smiled.

1218
01:20:46,719 --> 01:20:53,040
"We're going to stick up IP to the extent
necessary to pay for that fort—er—bank—on

1219
01:20:53,040 --> 01:20:54,590
Luna.

1220
01:20:54,590 --> 01:20:59,440
We'll also boost the price so that we'll make
enough to pay for those ships I'm having made.

1221
01:20:59,440 --> 01:21:01,360
The public will pay for that."

1222
01:21:01,360 --> 01:21:03,090
"I see.

1223
01:21:03,090 --> 01:21:06,170
And we aren't to stick the price too high,
and just make money?"

1224
01:21:06,170 --> 01:21:08,070
"That's the general idea."

1225
01:21:08,070 --> 01:21:13,920
"The IP Appropriations Board won't give you
what you need, Commander, for real improvements

1226
01:21:13,920 --> 01:21:15,620
on the IP ships?"

1227
01:21:15,620 --> 01:21:17,690
"They won't believe Kendall.

1228
01:21:17,690 --> 01:21:18,940
Therefore they won't."

1229
01:21:18,940 --> 01:21:22,460
"What did you mean about gamma rays, Buck?"

1230
01:21:22,460 --> 01:21:27,340
"Mercury will stop them and the Commander
here intends to have the refitted ships built

1231
01:21:27,340 --> 01:21:33,010
so that the engine room and control room are
one, and completely surrounded by the mercury

1232
01:21:33,010 --> 01:21:34,010
tanks.

1233
01:21:34,010 --> 01:21:37,030
The men will be protected against the gamma
rays."

1234
01:21:37,030 --> 01:21:42,170
"Won't the rays affect the power stored in
the mercury—perhaps release it?"

1235
01:21:42,170 --> 01:21:47,909
"We tried it out, of course, and while we
can't get the intensities we expect, and can't

1236
01:21:47,909 --> 01:21:52,480
really make any measurements of the gamma-ray
energy impinging on the mercury—it seems

1237
01:21:52,480 --> 01:21:55,710
to absorb, and store that energy!"

1238
01:21:55,710 --> 01:21:58,790
"What's next on the program, Buck?"

1239
01:21:58,790 --> 01:22:01,659
"Finish those ships I have building.

1240
01:22:01,659 --> 01:22:04,239
And I want to do some more development work.

1241
01:22:04,239 --> 01:22:08,540
The Stranger will return within six months
now, I believe.

1242
01:22:08,540 --> 01:22:13,260
It will take all that time, and more for real
refitting of the IP ships."

1243
01:22:13,260 --> 01:22:18,230
"How about more forts—or banks, whichever
you want to call them.

1244
01:22:18,230 --> 01:22:19,650
Mars isn't protected."

1245
01:22:19,650 --> 01:22:23,790
"Mars is abandoned," replied General Logan
seriously.

1246
01:22:23,790 --> 01:22:28,310
"We haven't any too much to protect old Earth,
and she must come first.

1247
01:22:28,310 --> 01:22:33,160
Mars will, of course, be protected as best
the IP ships can.

1248
01:22:33,160 --> 01:22:36,190
But—we're expecting defeat.

1249
01:22:36,190 --> 01:22:38,500
This isn't a case of glorious victory.

1250
01:22:38,500 --> 01:22:40,889
It will be a case of hard won survival.

1251
01:22:40,889 --> 01:22:46,530
We don't know anything about the enemy—except
that they are capable of interstellar flights,

1252
01:22:46,530 --> 01:22:48,130
and have atomic energy.

1253
01:22:48,130 --> 01:22:51,480
They are evidently far ahead of us.

1254
01:22:51,480 --> 01:22:54,310
Our battle is to survive till we learn how
to conquer.

1255
01:22:54,310 --> 01:23:00,150
For a time, at least, the Strangers will have
possession of most of the planets of the system.

1256
01:23:00,150 --> 01:23:05,409
We do not think they will be able to reach
Earth, because Commander McLaurin here will

1257
01:23:05,409 --> 01:23:10,630
withdraw his ships to Earth to protect the
planet—and the great 'Lunar Bank' will display

1258
01:23:10,630 --> 01:23:22,110
its true character."

1259
01:23:22,110 --> 01:23:35,650
VII
Faragaut looked unsympathetically at Buck

1260
01:23:35,650 --> 01:23:40,430
Kendall, as he stood glaring perplexedly at
the apparatus he had been working on.

1261
01:23:40,430 --> 01:23:44,320
"What's the matter, Buck, won't she perk?"

1262
01:23:44,320 --> 01:23:47,239
"No, damn it, and it should."

1263
01:23:47,239 --> 01:23:51,159
"That," pointed out Faragaut, "is just what
you think.

1264
01:23:51,159 --> 01:23:52,780
Nature thinks otherwise.

1265
01:23:52,780 --> 01:23:56,280
We generally have to abide by her opinions.

1266
01:23:56,280 --> 01:23:58,490
What is it—or what is it meant to be?"

1267
01:23:58,490 --> 01:23:59,960
"Perfect reflector."

1268
01:23:59,960 --> 01:24:02,929
"Make a nice mirror.

1269
01:24:02,929 --> 01:24:05,739
What else, and how come?"

1270
01:24:05,739 --> 01:24:08,969
"A mirror is just what I want.

1271
01:24:08,969 --> 01:24:13,619
I want something that will reflect all the
radiation that falls on it.

1272
01:24:13,619 --> 01:24:18,570
No metal will, even in its range of maximum
reflectivity.

1273
01:24:18,570 --> 01:24:22,990
Aluminum goes pretty high, silver, on some
ranges, a bit higher.

1274
01:24:22,990 --> 01:24:25,829
But none of them reaches 99%.

1275
01:24:25,829 --> 01:24:31,630
I want a perfect reflector that I can put
behind a source of wild, radiant energy so

1276
01:24:31,630 --> 01:24:35,969
I can focus it, and put it where it will do
the most good."

1277
01:24:35,969 --> 01:24:38,489
"Ninety-nine percent.

1278
01:24:38,489 --> 01:24:40,110
Sounds pretty good.

1279
01:24:40,110 --> 01:24:43,630
That's better efficiency than most anything
else we have, isn't it?"

1280
01:24:43,630 --> 01:24:45,510
"No, it isn't.

1281
01:24:45,510 --> 01:24:52,630
The accumulator is 100% efficient on the discharge,
and a good transformer, even before that,

1282
01:24:52,630 --> 01:24:55,240
ran as high as 99.8 sometimes.

1283
01:24:55,240 --> 01:24:56,620
They had to.

1284
01:24:56,620 --> 01:25:03,199
If you have a transformer handling 1,000,000
horsepower, and it's even 1% inefficient,

1285
01:25:03,199 --> 01:25:07,630
you have a heat loss of nearly 10,000 horsepower
to handle.

1286
01:25:07,630 --> 01:25:13,690
I want to use this as a destructive weapon,
and if I hand the other fellow energy in distressing

1287
01:25:13,690 --> 01:25:18,949
amounts, it's even worse at my end, because
no matter how perfect a beam I work out, there

1288
01:25:18,949 --> 01:25:21,449
will still be some spread.

1289
01:25:21,449 --> 01:25:25,760
I can make it mighty tight though, if I make
my surface a perfect parabola.

1290
01:25:25,760 --> 01:25:32,780
But if I send a million horse, I have to handle
it, and a ship can't stand several hundred

1291
01:25:32,780 --> 01:25:38,380
thousand horsepower roaming around loose as
heat, let alone the weapon itself.

1292
01:25:38,380 --> 01:25:41,270
The thing will be worse to me than to him.

1293
01:25:41,270 --> 01:25:46,400
"I figured there was something worth investigating
in those fields we developed on our magnetic

1294
01:25:46,400 --> 01:25:47,400
shield work.

1295
01:25:47,400 --> 01:25:50,860
They had to do, you know, with light, and
radiant energy.

1296
01:25:50,860 --> 01:25:54,420
There must be some reason why a metal reflects.

1297
01:25:54,420 --> 01:25:59,940
Further, though we can't get down to the basic
root of matter, the atom, yet, we can play

1298
01:25:59,940 --> 01:26:04,880
around just about as we please with molecules
and molecular forces.

1299
01:26:04,880 --> 01:26:10,530
But it is molecular force that determines
whether light and radiant energy of that caliber

1300
01:26:10,530 --> 01:26:12,800
shall be reflected or transmitted.

1301
01:26:12,800 --> 01:26:15,460
Take aluminum as an example.

1302
01:26:15,460 --> 01:26:19,790
In the metallic molecule state, the metal
will reflect pretty well.

1303
01:26:19,790 --> 01:26:23,780
But volatilize it, and it becomes transparent.

1304
01:26:23,780 --> 01:26:28,449
All gases are transparent, all metals reflective.

1305
01:26:28,449 --> 01:26:33,380
Then the secret of perfect reflection lies
at a molecular level in the organization of

1306
01:26:33,380 --> 01:26:36,510
matter, and is within our reach.

1307
01:26:36,510 --> 01:26:40,679
Well—this thing was supposed to make that
piece of silver reflective.

1308
01:26:40,679 --> 01:26:43,239
I missed it that time."

1309
01:26:43,239 --> 01:26:44,270
He sighed.

1310
01:26:44,270 --> 01:26:46,830
"I suppose I'll have to try again."

1311
01:26:46,830 --> 01:26:51,230
"I should think you'd use tungsten for that.

1312
01:26:51,230 --> 01:26:54,730
If you do have a slight leak, that would handle
the heat."

1313
01:26:54,730 --> 01:26:57,440
"No, it would hold it.

1314
01:26:57,440 --> 01:27:00,180
Silver is a better conductor of heat.

1315
01:27:00,180 --> 01:27:02,760
But the darned thing won't work."

1316
01:27:02,760 --> 01:27:05,159
"Your other scheme has."

1317
01:27:05,159 --> 01:27:06,200
Faragaut laughed.

1318
01:27:06,200 --> 01:27:08,730
"I came out principally for some signatures.

1319
01:27:08,730 --> 01:27:12,040
IP wants one hundred thousand tons of mercury.

1320
01:27:12,040 --> 01:27:15,199
I've sold most of mine already in the open
market.

1321
01:27:15,199 --> 01:27:16,230
You want to sell?"

1322
01:27:16,230 --> 01:27:17,230
"Certainly.

1323
01:27:17,230 --> 01:27:19,770
And I told you my price."

1324
01:27:19,770 --> 01:27:22,440
"I know," sighed Faragaut.

1325
01:27:22,440 --> 01:27:24,420
"It seems a shame though.

1326
01:27:24,420 --> 01:27:27,400
Those IP board men would pay higher.

1327
01:27:27,400 --> 01:27:32,679
And they're so damn tight it seems a crime
not to make 'em pay up when they have to."

1328
01:27:32,679 --> 01:27:35,840
"The IP will need the money worse elsewhere.

1329
01:27:35,840 --> 01:27:38,590
Where do I—oh, here?"

1330
01:27:38,590 --> 01:27:39,590
"Right.

1331
01:27:39,590 --> 01:27:40,660
I'll be out again this evening.

1332
01:27:40,660 --> 01:27:42,989
The regular group will be here?"

1333
01:27:42,989 --> 01:27:45,559
Kendall nodded as he signed in triplicate.

1334
01:27:45,559 --> 01:27:51,710
That evening, Buck had found the trouble in
his apparatus, for as he well knew, the theory

1335
01:27:51,710 --> 01:27:55,840
was right, only the practical apparatus needed
changing.

1336
01:27:55,840 --> 01:28:02,190
Before the group composed of Faragaut, McLaurin
and the members of Kendall's "bank," he demonstrated

1337
01:28:02,190 --> 01:28:04,260
it.

1338
01:28:04,260 --> 01:28:09,860
It was merely a small, model apparatus, with
a mirror of space-strained silver that was

1339
01:28:09,860 --> 01:28:12,989
an absolutely perfect reflector.

1340
01:28:12,989 --> 01:28:17,880
The mirror had been ground out of a block
of silver one foot deep, by four inches square,

1341
01:28:17,880 --> 01:28:23,460
carefully annealed, and the work had all been
done in a cooling bath.

1342
01:28:23,460 --> 01:28:29,520
The result was a mirror that was so nearly
a perfect paraboloid that the beam held sharp

1343
01:28:29,520 --> 01:28:34,670
and absolutely tight for the half-mile range
they tested it on.

1344
01:28:34,670 --> 01:28:38,320
At the projector it was three and one-half
inches in diameter.

1345
01:28:38,320 --> 01:28:43,070
At the target, it was three and fifty-two
one hundredths inches in diameter.

1346
01:28:43,070 --> 01:28:48,610
"Well, you've got the mirror, what are you
going to reflect with it now?" asked McLaurin.

1347
01:28:48,610 --> 01:28:52,719
"The greatest problem is getting a radiant
source, isn't it?

1348
01:28:52,719 --> 01:28:57,730
You can't get a temperature above about ten
thousand degrees, and maintain it very long,

1349
01:28:57,730 --> 01:28:59,060
can you?"

1350
01:28:59,060 --> 01:29:00,400
"Why not?"

1351
01:29:00,400 --> 01:29:01,400
Kendall smiled.

1352
01:29:01,400 --> 01:29:04,830
"It'll volatilize and leave the scene of action,
won't it?"

1353
01:29:04,830 --> 01:29:09,469
"What if it's a gaseous source already?"

1354
01:29:09,469 --> 01:29:10,980
"What?

1355
01:29:10,980 --> 01:29:13,139
Just a gas-flame?

1356
01:29:13,139 --> 01:29:15,449
That won't give you the point source you need.

1357
01:29:15,449 --> 01:29:20,140
You're using just a spotlight here, with a
Moregan Point-light.

1358
01:29:20,140 --> 01:29:24,550
That won't give you energy, and if you use
a gas-flame, the spread will be so great,

1359
01:29:24,550 --> 01:29:28,730
that no matter how perfectly you figure your
mirror, it won't beam."

1360
01:29:28,730 --> 01:29:31,849
"The answer is easy.

1361
01:29:31,849 --> 01:29:38,540
Not an ordinary gas-flame—a very extra-special
kind of gas-flame.

1362
01:29:38,540 --> 01:29:41,159
Know anything about Renwright's ionization-work?"

1363
01:29:41,159 --> 01:29:46,210
"Renwright—he's an IP man isn't he?"

1364
01:29:46,210 --> 01:29:47,210
"Right.

1365
01:29:47,210 --> 01:29:52,159
He's developed a system, which, thanks to
the power we can get in that atostor, will

1366
01:29:52,159 --> 01:29:55,110
sextuply ionize oxygen gas.

1367
01:29:55,110 --> 01:29:58,190
Now: what does that mean?"

1368
01:29:58,190 --> 01:30:01,900
"Spirits of space!

1369
01:30:01,900 --> 01:30:04,159
Concentrated essence of energy!"

1370
01:30:04,159 --> 01:30:05,719
"Right.

1371
01:30:05,719 --> 01:30:09,730
And in preparation, Cole here had one made
up for me.

1372
01:30:09,730 --> 01:30:11,829
That—and something else.

1373
01:30:11,829 --> 01:30:13,199
We'll just hook it up—"

1374
01:30:13,199 --> 01:30:19,880
With Devin's aid, Kendall attached the second
apparatus, a larger device into which the

1375
01:30:19,880 --> 01:30:23,170
silver block with its mirror surface fitted.

1376
01:30:23,170 --> 01:30:27,410
With the uttermost care, the two physicists
lined it up.

1377
01:30:27,410 --> 01:30:33,579
Two projectors pointed toward each other at
an angle, the base angles of a triangle, whose

1378
01:30:33,579 --> 01:30:36,119
apex was the center of the mirror.

1379
01:30:36,119 --> 01:30:40,800
On very low power, a soft, glowing violet
light filtered out through the opening of

1380
01:30:40,800 --> 01:30:45,230
the one, and a slight green light came from
the other.

1381
01:30:45,230 --> 01:30:49,780
But where the two streams met, an intense,
violet glare built up.

1382
01:30:49,780 --> 01:30:56,090
The center of action was not at the focus,
and slowly this was lined up, till a sharp,

1383
01:30:56,090 --> 01:31:00,980
violet beam of light reached out across the
open yard to the target set up.

1384
01:31:00,980 --> 01:31:05,520
Buck Kendall cut off the power, and slowly
got into position.

1385
01:31:05,520 --> 01:31:06,520
"Now.

1386
01:31:06,520 --> 01:31:08,030
Keep out from in front of that thing.

1387
01:31:08,030 --> 01:31:11,400
Put on these glasses—and watch out."

1388
01:31:11,400 --> 01:31:17,430
Heavy, thick-lensed orange-brown goggles were
passed out, and Kendall took his place.

1389
01:31:17,430 --> 01:31:23,860
Before him, a thick window of the same glass
had been arranged, so that he might see uninterruptedly

1390
01:31:23,860 --> 01:31:28,949
the controls at hand, and yet watch unblinded,
the action of the beam.

1391
01:31:28,949 --> 01:31:33,060
Dully the mirror-force relay clicked.

1392
01:31:33,060 --> 01:31:36,540
A hazy glow ran over the silver block, and
died.

1393
01:31:36,540 --> 01:31:43,880
Then—simultaneously the power was thrown
from two small, compact atostors into the

1394
01:31:43,880 --> 01:31:45,790
twin projectors.

1395
01:31:45,790 --> 01:31:52,849
Instantly—a titanic eruption of light almost
invisibly violet, spurted out in a solid,

1396
01:31:52,849 --> 01:31:54,150
compact stream.

1397
01:31:54,150 --> 01:32:00,159
With a roar and crash, it battered its way
through the thick air, and crashed into the

1398
01:32:00,159 --> 01:32:01,820
heavy target plate.

1399
01:32:01,820 --> 01:32:07,389
A stream of flame and scintillating sparks
erupted from the armor plate—and died as

1400
01:32:07,389 --> 01:32:09,639
Kendall cut the beam.

1401
01:32:09,639 --> 01:32:14,860
A white-hot area a foot across leaked down
the face of the metal.

1402
01:32:14,860 --> 01:32:18,860
"That," said Faragaut gently, removing his
goggles.

1403
01:32:18,860 --> 01:32:22,540
"That's not a spotlight, and it's not exactly
a gas-flame.

1404
01:32:22,540 --> 01:32:26,810
But I still don't know what that blue-hot
needle of destruction is.

1405
01:32:26,810 --> 01:32:30,949
Just what do you call that tame stellar furnace
of yours?"

1406
01:32:30,949 --> 01:32:37,120
"Not so far off, Tom," said Kendall happily,
"except that even S Doradus is cold compared

1407
01:32:37,120 --> 01:32:38,620
to that.

1408
01:32:38,620 --> 01:32:45,640
That sends almost pure ultra-violet light—which,
by the way, it is almost impossible to reflect

1409
01:32:45,640 --> 01:32:50,349
successfully, and represents a temperature
to be expressed not in thousands of degrees,

1410
01:32:50,349 --> 01:32:52,770
nor yet in tens of thousands.

1411
01:32:52,770 --> 01:32:57,790
I calculated the temperature would be about
750,000 degrees.

1412
01:32:57,790 --> 01:33:04,960
What is happening is that a stream of low-voltage
electrons—cathode rays—in great quantity

1413
01:33:04,960 --> 01:33:10,520
are meeting great quantities of sextuply ionized
oxygen.

1414
01:33:10,520 --> 01:33:16,560
That means that a nucleus used to having two
electrons in the K-ring, and six in the next,

1415
01:33:16,560 --> 01:33:22,780
has had that outer six knocked off, and then
has been hurled violently into free air.

1416
01:33:22,780 --> 01:33:30,100
"All by themselves, those sextuply ionized
oxygen atoms would have a good bit to say,

1417
01:33:30,100 --> 01:33:35,210
but they don't really begin to talk till they
start roaring for those electrons I'm feeding

1418
01:33:35,210 --> 01:33:36,400
them.

1419
01:33:36,400 --> 01:33:41,829
At the meeting point, they grab up all they
can get—probably about five—before the

1420
01:33:41,829 --> 01:33:46,670
competition and the fierce release of energy
drives them out, part-satisfied.

1421
01:33:46,670 --> 01:33:50,930
I lose a little energy there, but not a real
fraction.

1422
01:33:50,930 --> 01:33:55,660
It's the howl they put up for the first four
that counts.

1423
01:33:55,660 --> 01:34:01,739
The electron-feed is necessary, because otherwise
they'd smash on and ruin that mirror.

1424
01:34:01,739 --> 01:34:04,790
They work practically in a perfect vacuum.

1425
01:34:04,790 --> 01:34:07,590
That beam smashes the air out of the way.

1426
01:34:07,590 --> 01:34:10,809
Of course, in space it would work better."

1427
01:34:10,809 --> 01:34:14,460
"How could it?" asked Faragaut, faintly.

1428
01:34:14,460 --> 01:34:20,119
"Kendall," asked McLaurin, "can we install
that in the IP ships?"

1429
01:34:20,119 --> 01:34:21,790
"You can start."

1430
01:34:21,790 --> 01:34:22,790
Kendall shrugged.

1431
01:34:22,790 --> 01:34:24,110
"There isn't a lot of apparatus.

1432
01:34:24,110 --> 01:34:27,889
I'm going to install them in my ships, and
in the—bank.

1433
01:34:27,889 --> 01:34:31,190
I suspect—we haven't a lot of time left."

1434
01:34:31,190 --> 01:34:34,139
"How near ready are those ships?"

1435
01:34:34,139 --> 01:34:35,389
"About.

1436
01:34:35,389 --> 01:34:36,489
That's all I can say.

1437
01:34:36,489 --> 01:34:40,179
They've been torn up a bit for installation
of the atostor apparatus.

1438
01:34:40,179 --> 01:34:42,220
Now they'll have to be changed again."

1439
01:34:42,220 --> 01:34:45,329
"Anything more coming?"

1440
01:34:45,329 --> 01:34:47,929
Buck smiled slowly.

1441
01:34:47,929 --> 01:34:53,540
He turned directly to McLaurin and replied:
"Yes—the Strangers.

1442
01:34:53,540 --> 01:34:57,050
As to developments—I can't tell, naturally.

1443
01:34:57,050 --> 01:35:01,550
But if they do, it will be something entirely
unexpected now.

1444
01:35:01,550 --> 01:35:07,460
You see, given one new discovery, a half-dozen
will follow immediately from it.

1445
01:35:07,460 --> 01:35:10,990
When we announced that atostor, look what
happened.

1446
01:35:10,990 --> 01:35:15,489
Renwright must have thought it was God's gift
to suffering physicists.

1447
01:35:15,489 --> 01:35:18,870
He stuck some oxygen in the thing, added some
of his own stuff—and behold.

1448
01:35:18,870 --> 01:35:24,949
The magnetic apparatus gave us directly the
shield, and indirectly this mirror.

1449
01:35:24,949 --> 01:35:28,620
Now, I seem to have reached the end for the
time.

1450
01:35:28,620 --> 01:35:33,460
I'm still trying to get that space-release
for high speed—speed greater than light,

1451
01:35:33,460 --> 01:35:34,460
that is.

1452
01:35:34,460 --> 01:35:40,820
So far," he added bitterly, "all I've gotten
as an answer is a single expression that simply

1453
01:35:40,820 --> 01:35:44,820
means practical zero—Heisenberg's Uncertainty
Expression."

1454
01:35:44,820 --> 01:35:51,289
"I'm uncertain as to your meaning"—McLaurin
smiled—"but I take it that's nothing new."

1455
01:35:51,289 --> 01:35:52,289
"No.

1456
01:35:52,289 --> 01:35:56,280
Nearly four centuries old—twentieth century
physics.

1457
01:35:56,280 --> 01:36:02,739
I'll have to try some other line of attack,
I guess, but that did seem so darned right.

1458
01:36:02,739 --> 01:36:04,370
It just sounded right.

1459
01:36:04,370 --> 01:36:10,059
Something ought to happen—and it just keeps
saying 'nothing more except the natural uncertainty

1460
01:36:10,059 --> 01:36:11,059
of nature.'"

1461
01:36:11,059 --> 01:36:15,520
"Try it out, your math might be wrong somewhere."

1462
01:36:15,520 --> 01:36:16,520
Kendall laughed.

1463
01:36:16,520 --> 01:36:18,739
"If it was—I'd hate to try it out.

1464
01:36:18,739 --> 01:36:22,280
If it wasn't I'd have no reason to.

1465
01:36:22,280 --> 01:36:23,940
And there's plenty of other work to do.

1466
01:36:23,940 --> 01:36:27,270
For one thing, getting that apparatus in production.

1467
01:36:27,270 --> 01:36:29,320
The IP board won't like me."

1468
01:36:29,320 --> 01:36:30,320
Kendall smiled.

1469
01:36:30,320 --> 01:36:33,280
"They don't," replied McLaurin.

1470
01:36:33,280 --> 01:36:39,630
"They're getting more and more and more worried—but
they've got to keep the IP fleet in such condition

1471
01:36:39,630 --> 01:36:44,210
that it can at least catch an up-to-date freighter."

1472
01:36:44,210 --> 01:36:52,349
Gresth Gkae looked back at Sthor rapidly dropping
behind, and across at her sister world, Asthor,

1473
01:36:52,349 --> 01:36:55,369
circling a bare 100,000 miles away.

1474
01:36:55,369 --> 01:37:01,840
Behind his great interstellar cruiser came
a long line of similar ships.

1475
01:37:01,840 --> 01:37:07,820
Each was loaded now not with instruments and
pure scientists, but with weapons, fuel and

1476
01:37:07,820 --> 01:37:08,820
warriors.

1477
01:37:08,820 --> 01:37:11,909
Colonists too, came in the last ships.

1478
01:37:11,909 --> 01:37:15,080
One hundred and fifty giant ships.

1479
01:37:15,080 --> 01:37:21,720
All the wealth of Sthor and Asthor had been
concentrated in producing those great machines.

1480
01:37:21,720 --> 01:37:25,770
Every one represented nearly the equivalent
of thirty million Earth-dollars.

1481
01:37:25,770 --> 01:37:31,000
Four and a half billions of dollars for mere
materials.

1482
01:37:31,000 --> 01:37:36,130
Gresth Gkae had the honor of lead position,
for he had discovered the planets and their

1483
01:37:36,130 --> 01:37:38,460
stable, though tiny, sun.

1484
01:37:38,460 --> 01:37:45,360
Still, Gresth Gkae knew his own giant Mira
was a super-giant sun—and a curse and a

1485
01:37:45,360 --> 01:37:48,180
menace to any rational society.

1486
01:37:48,180 --> 01:37:54,610
Our yellow-white sun (to his eyes, an almost
invisible color, similar to our blue) was

1487
01:37:54,610 --> 01:37:57,890
small, but stable, and warm enough.

1488
01:37:57,890 --> 01:38:04,620
In half an hour, all the ships were in space,
and at a given signal, at ten-second intervals,

1489
01:38:04,620 --> 01:38:08,929
they sprang into the superspeed, faster than
light.

1490
01:38:08,929 --> 01:38:14,809
For an instant, giant Mira ran and seemed
distorted, as though seen through a porthole

1491
01:38:14,809 --> 01:38:19,950
covered with running water, then steadied,
curiously distorted.

1492
01:38:19,950 --> 01:38:25,020
Faster than light they raced across the galaxy.

1493
01:38:25,020 --> 01:38:29,840
Even in their super-fast ships, nearly three
and a half weeks passed before the sun they

1494
01:38:29,840 --> 01:38:34,390
sought, singled itself from the star-field
as an extra bright point.

1495
01:38:34,390 --> 01:38:38,929
Two days more, and the sun was within planetary
distance.

1496
01:38:38,929 --> 01:38:44,630
They came at an angle to the plane of the
ecliptic, but they leveled down to it now,

1497
01:38:44,630 --> 01:38:48,469
and slanted toward giant Jupiter and Jovian
worlds.

1498
01:38:48,469 --> 01:38:54,670
Ten worlds, in one sweep, it was—four habitable
worlds.

1499
01:38:54,670 --> 01:39:00,860
The nine satellites would be converted into
forts at once, nine space-sweeping forts guarding

1500
01:39:00,860 --> 01:39:03,039
the approaches to the planet.

1501
01:39:03,039 --> 01:39:08,559
Gresth Gkae had made a fairly good search
of the worlds, and knew that Earth was the

1502
01:39:08,559 --> 01:39:11,679
main home of civilization in this system.

1503
01:39:11,679 --> 01:39:13,710
Mars was second, and Venus third.

1504
01:39:13,710 --> 01:39:19,239
But Jupiter offered the greatest possibilities
for quick settlement, a base from which they

1505
01:39:19,239 --> 01:39:24,960
could more easily operate, a base for fuels,
for the heavy elements they would need—

1506
01:39:24,960 --> 01:39:31,039
Fifteen million miles from Jupiter they slowed
below the speed of light—and the IP stations

1507
01:39:31,039 --> 01:39:32,599
observed them.

1508
01:39:32,599 --> 01:39:38,889
Instantly, according to instructions issued
by Commander McLaurin, a fleet of ten of the

1509
01:39:38,889 --> 01:39:41,870
