01:58:54,720 --> 01:58:56,960
from now on.

1789
01:58:56,960 --> 01:58:58,870
You may have a lot of power—but."

1790
01:58:58,870 --> 01:59:04,210
"But—we also have those new fifteen-foot
UV beams.

1791
01:59:04,210 --> 01:59:10,910
And one fifteen-foot UV beam is worth, theoretically,
nine five-foot beams, and practically, a dozen.

1792
01:59:10,910 --> 01:59:12,540
We have a dozen of them.

1793
01:59:12,540 --> 01:59:18,369
Remember, this place was designed not only
to protect itself, but Earth, too."

1794
01:59:18,369 --> 01:59:20,949
"They can still pull, can't they?"

1795
01:59:20,949 --> 01:59:24,540
"They'll stop pulling when they get their
fingers burned.

1796
01:59:24,540 --> 01:59:29,019
In the meantime, why not use some of those
IP ships to bring in a few more cargoes of

1797
01:59:29,019 --> 01:59:30,219
charged mercury?"

1798
01:59:30,219 --> 01:59:33,030
"They aren't good for much else, are they?

1799
01:59:33,030 --> 01:59:36,789
I wonder if those fellows have anything more
we don't know?"

1800
01:59:36,789 --> 01:59:39,260
"Oh, probably.

1801
01:59:39,260 --> 01:59:41,309
I'm going to work on that crumbler thing.

1802
01:59:41,309 --> 01:59:43,510
That's the first consideration now."

1803
01:59:43,510 --> 01:59:44,510
"Why?"

1804
01:59:44,510 --> 01:59:47,090
"So we can move a ship.

1805
01:59:47,090 --> 01:59:50,000
As it is, even those two we built aren't any
good."

1806
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:52,880
"Would they be anyway?"

1807
01:59:52,880 --> 01:59:57,210
"Well—I think I might disturb those gentlemen
slightly.

1808
01:59:57,210 --> 02:00:02,349
Remember, they each have a nose-beam eighteen
feet across.

1809
02:00:02,349 --> 02:00:04,060
Exceedingly unpleasant customers."

1810
02:00:04,060 --> 02:00:11,409
"Score: Strangers; magnetic field, atomic
bombs, atomic power, crumbler ray.

1811
02:00:11,409 --> 02:00:15,000
Home team; UV beams."

1812
02:00:15,000 --> 02:00:16,000
Kendall grinned.

1813
02:00:16,000 --> 02:00:19,329
"I'd heard you were a pessimistic cuss when
battle started—"

1814
02:00:19,329 --> 02:00:22,289
"Pessimistic, hell, I'm merely counting things
up."

1815
02:00:22,289 --> 02:00:27,829
"McClellan had all the odds on Lee back in
the Civil War of the States—but Lee sent

1816
02:00:27,829 --> 02:00:30,099
him home faster than he came."

1817
02:00:30,099 --> 02:00:32,400
"But Lee lost in the end."

1818
02:00:32,400 --> 02:00:33,769
"Why bring that up?

1819
02:00:33,769 --> 02:00:35,770
I've got work to do."

1820
02:00:35,770 --> 02:00:40,369
Still smiling, Kendall went to the laboratory
he had built up in the "Lunar Bank."

1821
02:00:40,369 --> 02:00:42,789
Devin was already there, calculating.

1822
02:00:42,789 --> 02:00:44,420
He looked unhappy.

1823
02:00:44,420 --> 02:00:48,119
"We can't do anything, as far as I can see.

1824
02:00:48,119 --> 02:00:51,080
They're using an electric field all right,
and projecting it.

1825
02:00:51,080 --> 02:00:53,449
I can't see how we can do that."

1826
02:00:53,449 --> 02:00:58,449
"Neither can I," agreed Kendall, "so we can't
use that weapon.

1827
02:00:58,449 --> 02:01:00,050
I really didn't want to anyway.

1828
02:01:00,050 --> 02:01:04,861
Like the neutron gun which I told Commander
McLaurin would be useless as a weapon, they'd

1829
02:01:04,861 --> 02:01:07,860
be prepared for it, you can be sure.

1830
02:01:07,860 --> 02:01:12,020
All I want to do is fight it, and make their
projection useless."

1831
02:01:12,020 --> 02:01:17,150
"Well, we have to know how they project it
before we can break up the projection, don't

1832
02:01:17,150 --> 02:01:18,150
we?"

1833
02:01:18,150 --> 02:01:19,179
"Not at all.

1834
02:01:19,179 --> 02:01:23,869
They're using an electric field of very high
frequency, but variable frequency.

1835
02:01:23,869 --> 02:01:30,400
As far as I can see, all we need is a similar
variable electric field of a slightly different

1836
02:01:30,400 --> 02:01:34,760
frequency to heterodyne theirs into something
quite harmless."

1837
02:01:34,760 --> 02:01:36,420
"Oh," said Devin.

1838
02:01:36,420 --> 02:01:38,739
"We could, couldn't we?

1839
02:01:38,739 --> 02:01:40,120
But how are you going to do that?"

1840
02:01:40,120 --> 02:01:44,059
"We'll have to learn, that's all."

1841
02:01:44,059 --> 02:01:46,949
Buck Kendall started trying to learn.

1842
02:01:46,949 --> 02:01:51,880
In the meantime, the Mirans were taking over
Jupiter.

1843
02:01:51,880 --> 02:01:56,260
There were three IP stations on the planet
itself, but they were vastly hindered by the

1844
02:01:56,260 --> 02:02:00,059
thick, almost ultra-violet-proof atmosphere
of Jupiter.

1845
02:02:00,059 --> 02:02:01,849
Their rays were weak.

1846
02:02:01,849 --> 02:02:05,260
And the magnetic fields of the Mirans were
unaffected.

1847
02:02:05,260 --> 02:02:09,389
Only their atomic bombs were hindered by the
heavier gravity that pulled the rocks back

1848
02:02:09,389 --> 02:02:12,770
in place faster than the bombs could throw
them out.

1849
02:02:12,770 --> 02:02:18,429
Still—a few hours of work, and the IP stations
on Jupiter had rolled wildly across the flat

1850
02:02:18,429 --> 02:02:23,280
plains of the planet like dented cans, to
end in utter destruction.

1851
02:02:23,280 --> 02:02:27,639
The Mirans had paid no attention to the fleeing
passenger and freighter ships that left the

1852
02:02:27,639 --> 02:02:32,389
planet, loaded to the utmost with human cargo,
and absolutely no freight.

1853
02:02:32,389 --> 02:02:37,410
The IP fleet had to go to their rescue with
oxygen tanks to take care of the extra humans,

1854
02:02:37,410 --> 02:02:42,119
but nearly three-quarters of the population
of Jupiter, a newly established population,

1855
02:02:42,119 --> 02:02:45,340
and hence a readily mobile one, was saved.

1856
02:02:45,340 --> 02:02:49,150
The others, the Mirans did not bother with
particularly except when they happened to

1857
02:02:49,150 --> 02:02:51,849
be near where the Mirans wanted to work.

1858
02:02:51,849 --> 02:02:55,450
Then they were instantly destroyed by atomic
bombing, or gamma rays.

1859
02:02:55,450 --> 02:03:01,179
The Mirans settled almost at once, and began
their work of finding on Jupiter the badly

1860
02:03:01,179 --> 02:03:03,059
needed atomic fuels.

1861
02:03:03,059 --> 02:03:09,250
Machines were set up, and work begun, Mirans
laboring under the gravity of the heavy planet.

1862
02:03:09,250 --> 02:03:14,570
Then, fifty ships swam up again, reloaded
with fuel, and with crews consisting solely

1863
02:03:14,570 --> 02:03:18,770
of uninjured warriors, and started for Mars.

1864
02:03:18,770 --> 02:03:23,789
Mars was half way between her near conjunction
and her maximum elongation with respect to

1865
02:03:23,789 --> 02:03:25,690
Jupiter at that time.

1866
02:03:25,690 --> 02:03:30,840
The Mirans knew their business though, for
they started in on the IP station on Phobos.

1867
02:03:30,840 --> 02:03:36,520
They were practiced by this time, and this
IP station had only seven five-foot beams.

1868
02:03:36,520 --> 02:03:41,830
In half an hour that station fell, and its
sister station on Deimos followed.

1869
02:03:41,830 --> 02:03:46,119
Three wounded ships returned to Jupiter, and
ten new ships came out.

1870
02:03:46,119 --> 02:03:50,260
The attack on Mars itself was started.

1871
02:03:50,260 --> 02:03:51,719
Mars was a different proposition.

1872
02:03:51,719 --> 02:03:58,410
There were thirty-two IP stations here, one
of them nearly as powerful as the Lunar Bank

1873
02:03:58,410 --> 02:03:59,410
station.

1874
02:03:59,410 --> 02:04:03,639
It was equipped with four of the huge fifteen-foot
beams.

1875
02:04:03,639 --> 02:04:08,750
And it had fifteen tons of mercury, more than
seven-eighths charged.

1876
02:04:08,750 --> 02:04:14,099
The Mars Center Station was located a short
ten miles from the Mars Center City, and under

1877
02:04:14,099 --> 02:04:18,719
the immediate orders of the IP heads, Mars
Center City had been vacated.

1878
02:04:18,719 --> 02:04:26,230
For two days the Mirans hung off Mars, solidifying
their positions on Phobos and Deimos.

1879
02:04:26,230 --> 02:04:29,900
Then, with sixty-two ships, they attacked.

1880
02:04:29,900 --> 02:04:35,130
They had made some very astute observations,
and they started on the smaller stations just

1881
02:04:35,130 --> 02:04:38,190
beyond the range of the Mars Center Station.

1882
02:04:38,190 --> 02:04:42,869
Naturally, near so powerful a center, these
stations had never been strong.

1883
02:04:42,869 --> 02:04:44,420
They fell rapidly.

1884
02:04:44,420 --> 02:04:48,869
But they had been counted on by Mars Center
as auxiliary supports.

1885
02:04:48,869 --> 02:04:53,699
McLaurin had sent very definite orders to
Mars Center forbidding any action on their

1886
02:04:53,699 --> 02:04:56,780
part, save gathering of power-supplies.

1887
02:04:56,780 --> 02:05:01,050
At last the direct attack on Mars Center was
launched.

1888
02:05:01,050 --> 02:05:05,750
For the first time, the Mirans saw one of
the fifteen-foot beams.

1889
02:05:05,750 --> 02:05:09,059
Mars' atmosphere is thin, and there is little
ozone.

1890
02:05:09,059 --> 02:05:12,880
The ultra-violet beams were nearly as effective
as in empty space.

1891
02:05:12,880 --> 02:05:18,670
When the Mirans dropped their ships, a full
thirty of them, into the circle formation,

1892
02:05:18,670 --> 02:05:20,909
Mars Center answered at once.

1893
02:05:20,909 --> 02:05:24,300
All four beams started.

1894
02:05:24,300 --> 02:05:30,110
Those fifteen-foot beams, connected directly
to huge atostor release apparatus, delivered

1895
02:05:30,110 --> 02:05:34,079
a maximum power of two and three-quarter billion
horsepower, each.

1896
02:05:34,079 --> 02:05:40,570
The first Miran ship struck, sparkled magnificently,
and a terrific cascade of white-hot metal

1897
02:05:40,570 --> 02:05:42,400
rolled down from its nose.

1898
02:05:42,400 --> 02:05:47,909
The great ship nosed down and to the left
abruptly, accelerated swiftly—and crashed

1899
02:05:47,909 --> 02:05:51,920
with tremendous energy on the plain outside
of Mars Center City.

1900
02:05:51,920 --> 02:05:57,829
White, unwavering flames licked up suddenly,
and made a column five hundred feet high against

1901
02:05:57,829 --> 02:05:59,650
the dark sky.

1902
02:05:59,650 --> 02:06:04,790
Then the wreck exploded with a violence that
left a crater half a mile across.

1903
02:06:04,790 --> 02:06:07,929
Three other ships had been struck, and were
rapidly retreating.

1904
02:06:07,929 --> 02:06:13,730
Another try was made for the ring formation,
and four more ships were wounded, and replaced.

1905
02:06:13,730 --> 02:06:18,619
The ring did not retreat, but the great magnetic
field started.

1906
02:06:18,619 --> 02:06:24,170
Atomic and gamma ray bombs started now, flashing
sometimes dangerously close to the station

1907
02:06:24,170 --> 02:06:28,769
as its magnetic field battled the rotating
field of the ships.

1908
02:06:28,769 --> 02:06:33,080
The four greater beams, and many smaller ones
were in swift and angry action.

1909
02:06:33,080 --> 02:06:38,659
Not more than a ten-second exposure could
be endured by any one ship, before it must

1910
02:06:38,659 --> 02:06:40,059
retreat.

1911
02:06:40,059 --> 02:06:44,469
For five minutes the Mirans hung doggedly
at their task.

1912
02:06:44,469 --> 02:06:47,420
Then, wisely, they retreated.

1913
02:06:47,420 --> 02:06:51,889
Of the fleet, not more than seven ships remained
untouched.

1914
02:06:51,889 --> 02:06:56,639
Mars Center Station had held—at what cost
only they knew.

1915
02:06:56,639 --> 02:07:01,670
Five hundred tons of their mercury had been
exhausted in that brief five minutes.

1916
02:07:01,670 --> 02:07:06,000
One hundred tons a minute had flowed into
and out of the atostor apparatus.

1917
02:07:06,000 --> 02:07:10,309
Mars Center radioed for help, when the fleet
lifted.

1918
02:07:10,309 --> 02:07:16,120
There was one other station on Mars that stood
a good chance of survival, Deenmor Station,

1919
02:07:16,120 --> 02:07:21,110
with three of the big beams installed, and
apparatus for their fourth was in the station,

1920
02:07:21,110 --> 02:07:24,070
and being rapidly worked over.

1921
02:07:24,070 --> 02:07:28,469
McLaurin did a wise and courageous thing,
at which every man on Mars cursed.

1922
02:07:28,469 --> 02:07:34,980
He ordered that all IP stations save these
two be deserted, and all mercury fuel reserves

1923
02:07:34,980 --> 02:07:39,139
be moved to Deenmor and Mars Center.

1924
02:07:39,139 --> 02:07:44,599
The Mirans could not land on the North Western
section of Mars, nor in the South Central

1925
02:07:44,599 --> 02:07:45,599
region.

1926
02:07:45,599 --> 02:07:50,130
Therefore Mars was not exactly habitable to
Miran ships, because the great beams had been

1927
02:07:50,130 --> 02:07:55,679
so perfectly figured that they were effective
at a range of nearly twelve hundred miles.

1928
02:07:55,679 --> 02:08:00,699
Deenmor station was attacked—but it was
a half-hearted attack, for Mirans were becoming

1929
02:08:00,699 --> 02:08:04,550
distinctly skittish about fifteen-foot UV
beams.

1930
02:08:04,550 --> 02:08:09,050
Two badly blistered ships—and the Mirans
retreated to Jupiter.

1931
02:08:09,050 --> 02:08:11,980
But Mira held Phobos and Deimos.

1932
02:08:11,980 --> 02:08:17,230
In two weeks, they had set up cannon there,
and proved themselves accurate long-range

1933
02:08:17,230 --> 02:08:18,230
gunners.

1934
02:08:18,230 --> 02:08:22,900
Against the feeble attraction of Deimos, and
with Mars' gravity to help them, they began

1935
02:08:22,900 --> 02:08:27,510
bombarding the two stations, and anything
that attempted to approach them, with gamma

1936
02:08:27,510 --> 02:08:30,489
and atomic explosive bombs.

1937
02:08:30,489 --> 02:08:35,599
Meanwhile they amused themselves occasionally
by planting a gamma-ray bomb in each of Mars'

1938
02:08:35,599 --> 02:08:36,650
major cities.

1939
02:08:36,650 --> 02:08:42,690
They made Mars uninhabitable for Solarians
as well as for Mirans, at least until the

1940
02:08:42,690 --> 02:08:48,639
deadly slow-action atomic explosives wore
off, or were removed.

1941
02:08:48,639 --> 02:08:54,429
Then the Mirans, after a lapse of three weeks
while they dug in their toes on Jupiter, prepared

1942
02:08:54,429 --> 02:08:55,429
to leap.

1943
02:08:55,429 --> 02:08:57,890
Earth was the next goal.

1944
02:08:57,890 --> 02:09:02,499
Miran scout-ships had been sent out before
this—and severely handled by the concentrated

1945
02:09:02,499 --> 02:09:06,949
fleets of the IP that hung grimly off Earth
and Luna now.

1946
02:09:06,949 --> 02:09:09,210
But the scouts had learned one thing.

1947
02:09:09,210 --> 02:09:14,699
Mirans could never hope to attain a firm grasp
on Earth while terribly armed Luna hung like

1948
02:09:14,699 --> 02:09:17,520
a Sword of Damocles over their heads.

1949
02:09:17,520 --> 02:09:22,880
Further, attack on Earth directly would be
next to impossible, for, thanks to Faragaut's

1950
02:09:22,880 --> 02:09:28,400
Interplanetary Company, nearly all the mercury
metal in the system was safely lodged on Earth,

1951
02:09:28,400 --> 02:09:30,480
and saturated with power.

1952
02:09:30,480 --> 02:09:35,059
Every major city had been equipped with great
UV apparatus.

1953
02:09:35,059 --> 02:09:40,850
And neutron guns in plenty waited on small
ships just outside the atmosphere to explode

1954
02:09:40,850 --> 02:09:46,159
harmlessly any atomic or gamma bombs Miran
ships might attempt to deposit.

1955
02:09:46,159 --> 02:09:49,610
An attack on Luna was the first step.

1956
02:09:49,610 --> 02:09:54,800
But that terrible, gigantic fort on Luna worried
them.

1957
02:09:54,800 --> 02:09:59,980
Yet while that fort existed, Earth ships were
free to come and go, for Mirans could not

1958
02:09:59,980 --> 02:10:02,409
afford to stand near.

1959
02:10:02,409 --> 02:10:07,139
At a distance of twenty thousand miles, small
Miran ships had felt the touch of those great

1960
02:10:07,139 --> 02:10:08,540
UV beams.

1961
02:10:08,540 --> 02:10:14,050
Finally, a brief test-attack was made, with
an entire fleet of one hundred ships.

1962
02:10:14,050 --> 02:10:18,780
They drew almost into position, faster than
light, faster than the signaling warnings

1963
02:10:18,780 --> 02:10:20,450
could send their messages.

1964
02:10:20,450 --> 02:10:26,630
In position, all those great ships strained
and heaved at the mighty magnetic vortex that

1965
02:10:26,630 --> 02:10:29,010
twisted at the field of the fort.

1966
02:10:29,010 --> 02:10:33,790
Instantly, twelve of the fifteen-foot UV beams
replied.

1967
02:10:33,790 --> 02:10:39,100
And—two great UV beams of a size the Mirans
had never seen before, beams from the two

1968
02:10:39,100 --> 02:10:43,800
ships, "S Doradus" and "Cepheid."

1969
02:10:43,800 --> 02:10:47,670
The test-attack dissolved as suddenly as it
had come.

1970
02:10:47,670 --> 02:10:51,949
The Mirans returned to Jupiter, and to the
outer planets where they had further established

1971
02:10:51,949 --> 02:10:53,280
themselves.

1972
02:10:53,280 --> 02:10:55,710
Most of the Solar system was theirs.

1973
02:10:55,710 --> 02:11:00,860
But the Solarians still held the choicest
planets—and kept the Mirans from using the

1974
02:11:00,860 --> 02:11:08,640
mild-temperatured Mars.

1975
02:11:08,640 --> 02:11:24,219
IX
"They can't take this, at least," sighed McLaurin

1976
02:11:24,219 --> 02:11:26,199
as they retreated from Luna.

1977
02:11:26,199 --> 02:11:29,190
"I didn't think they could—right away.

1978
02:11:29,190 --> 02:11:32,999
I'm wondering though if they haven't something
we haven't seen yet.

1979
02:11:32,999 --> 02:11:36,380
Besides which—give them time, give them
time."

1980
02:11:36,380 --> 02:11:40,429
"Well, give us time, too," snapped McLaurin.

1981
02:11:40,429 --> 02:11:42,980
"How are you coming?"

1982
02:11:42,980 --> 02:11:44,010
Buck smiled.

1983
02:11:44,010 --> 02:11:46,030
"I'm sure I don't know.

1984
02:11:46,030 --> 02:11:51,530
I have a machine but I haven't the slightest
idea of whether or not it's any good."

1985
02:11:51,530 --> 02:11:53,230
"Why not?"

1986
02:11:53,230 --> 02:11:58,260
"I can destroy—I hope—but I can't build
up their ray.

1987
02:11:58,260 --> 02:12:02,760
I can't test the machine because I haven't
their ray to test it against."

1988
02:12:02,760 --> 02:12:05,090
"What can we do to test it?"

1989
02:12:05,090 --> 02:12:10,099
"The only thing I can see is to call for volunteers—and
send out a six-man cruiser.

1990
02:12:10,099 --> 02:12:14,880
If the ship's too small, they may not destroy
it with the big crumbler rays.

1991
02:12:14,880 --> 02:12:21,119
If it's too large—and the machine didn't
work—we'd lose too much."

1992
02:12:21,119 --> 02:12:25,130
Twelve hours later, the IP men at the Lunar
Bank fort were lined up.

1993
02:12:25,130 --> 02:12:32,099
McLaurin stepped up on the platform, and addressed
the men briefly, told them what was needed.

1994
02:12:32,099 --> 02:12:36,901
Six volunteers were selected by a process
of elimination, those who were married, had

1995
02:12:36,901 --> 02:12:40,140
dependents, officers, and others were refused.

1996
02:12:40,140 --> 02:12:46,809
Finally, six men of the IP were chosen, neither
rookies nor veterans, six average men.

1997
02:12:46,809 --> 02:12:52,219
And one average six-man cruiser, one hundred
and eleven feet long, twenty-two in diameter.

1998
02:12:52,219 --> 02:12:59,999
It was the T-208, a sister ship of the T-247,
the first ship to be destroyed.

1999
02:12:59,999 --> 02:13:07,670
The T-208 started out from Luna, and with
full acceleration, sped out toward Phobos.

2000
02:13:07,670 --> 02:13:12,150
Slowly she circled the satellite, while distant
scouts kept her under view.

2001
02:13:12,150 --> 02:13:19,429
Lazily, the Miran patrol on Phobos watched
the T-208, indifferent to her.

2002
02:13:19,429 --> 02:13:25,640
The T-208 dove suddenly, after five fruitless
circles of the tiny world, and with her four-foot

2003
02:13:25,640 --> 02:13:30,940
UV beam flaming, stabbed angrily at a flight
of Miran scouts berthed in the very shadow

2004
02:13:30,940 --> 02:13:36,289
of a great battle cruiser, one of the interstellar
ships stationed here on Phobos.

