02:28:36,660 --> 02:28:39,160
We've got to take it and like it."

2227
02:28:39,160 --> 02:28:43,580
"But," objected McLaurin, "we don't like it."

2228
02:28:43,580 --> 02:28:47,939
"Then build ships as big as his, and he'll
quit trying to roast you.

2229
02:28:47,939 --> 02:28:51,260
Particularly if the inner walls are synthetic
plastics.

2230
02:28:51,260 --> 02:28:55,840
Did you know I used them in the 'S Doradus'
and 'Cepheid'?"

2231
02:28:55,840 --> 02:28:56,840
"Yes.

2232
02:28:56,840 --> 02:28:58,750
Were you thinking of that?"

2233
02:28:58,750 --> 02:29:04,010
"No—just luck—and the fact that they're
light, strong as steel almost, and can be

2234
02:29:04,010 --> 02:29:07,280
manufactured in forms much more quickly.

2235
02:29:07,280 --> 02:29:09,950
Only the outer hull is tungsten-beryllium.

2236
02:29:09,950 --> 02:29:15,340
The advantage in this will be that nearly
all the energy will be absorbed outside, and

2237
02:29:15,340 --> 02:29:20,910
we'll radiate pretty fast, particularly as
that tungsten-beryllium has a high radiation-factor

2238
02:29:20,910 --> 02:29:22,620
in the long heat range."

2239
02:29:22,620 --> 02:29:24,819
"What does that mean?"

2240
02:29:24,819 --> 02:29:29,700
"Well, ordinary polished silver is a mighty
poor radiator.

2241
02:29:29,700 --> 02:29:35,300
Homely example: Try waiting for your coffee
to cool if it's in a polished silver pot.

2242
02:29:35,300 --> 02:29:38,780
Then try it in a tungsten-beryllium pot.

2243
02:29:38,780 --> 02:29:44,240
No matter how you polish that tungsten-beryllium,
the stuff WILL radiate heat.

2244
02:29:44,240 --> 02:29:48,220
That's why an IP ship is always so blamed
cold.

2245
02:29:48,220 --> 02:29:52,359
You know the passenger ships use polished
aluminum outer walls.

2246
02:29:52,359 --> 02:29:57,040
The big help is, that the tungsten-beryllium
will throw off the energy pretty fast, and

2247
02:29:57,040 --> 02:30:01,920
in a big ship, with a whale of a lot of matter
